1
00:00:04,107 --> 00:00:12,477
Hello!

2
00:00:15,668 --> 00:00:18,550
Hello all, thank you for coming.

3
00:00:18,550 --> 00:00:23,413
My name is Warren Davis, and 40 years ago this year,

4
00:00:23,413 --> 00:00:28,836
I made a little game with some help called Qbert.

5
00:00:28,836 --> 00:00:30,477
And that is what I'm here to talk about.

6
00:00:30,477 --> 00:00:34,359
It's very, especially lovely for me to be here

7
00:00:34,359 --> 00:00:35,620
at the 40th anniversary.

8
00:00:37,121 --> 00:00:45,824
And if you don't know that much about me, which is very likely, I'm going to go through a little bit of my career in the world of video games.

9
00:00:45,824 --> 00:00:54,007
After Qubit was my first game. After Qubit, I did a Laserdisc game for the same company, Gottlieb, called Us vs. Them.

10
00:00:54,007 --> 00:00:57,309
I moved to Williams, and while I was there I worked on Joust 2.

11
00:00:57,309 --> 00:01:02,771
Also did a Redemption game as a consultant called Lotto Fun.

12
00:01:03,451 --> 00:01:04,972
which I'm sure you've never heard of,

13
00:01:04,972 --> 00:01:07,192
unless maybe you grew up on the Jersey Shore,

14
00:01:07,192 --> 00:01:09,013
and then you might've.

15
00:01:09,013 --> 00:01:11,074
I worked for Premier Technology,

16
00:01:11,074 --> 00:01:14,615
which was an offshoot of Gottlieb after Gottlieb closed,

17
00:01:14,615 --> 00:01:16,256
and they decided to make a video game,

18
00:01:16,256 --> 00:01:21,538
and so that turned into an arcade game called Exterminator,

19
00:01:21,538 --> 00:01:24,759
which I could probably do a whole hour on in itself.

20
00:01:24,759 --> 00:01:26,440
Fans of Exterminator?

21
00:01:26,440 --> 00:01:27,020
Hard to believe.

22
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,362
I'm back at Williams and I worked on,

23
00:01:33,362 --> 00:01:35,824
I was on the teams that did Terminator 2

24
00:01:35,824 --> 00:01:38,666
and Revolution X featuring Aerosmith.

25
00:01:40,817 --> 00:01:42,098
Don't laugh, they were really in it.

26
00:01:42,098 --> 00:01:47,860
And then the other thing that I'm sort of known for is I created the digitizing system

27
00:01:47,860 --> 00:01:53,883
that allowed actors to be digitized and put into all of the Williams Valley Midway games

28
00:01:53,883 --> 00:01:55,283
of the 90s.

29
00:01:55,283 --> 00:02:01,206
And then I left the arcade industry and I worked for Disney Interactive for a while.

30
00:02:01,206 --> 00:02:03,887
I was an Imagineer for four months.

31
00:02:03,887 --> 00:02:05,608
I worked on the ill-fated...

32
00:02:06,128 --> 00:02:11,395
And that's putting it kindly, Spyro, Enter the Dragonfly, another, that's probably a

33
00:02:11,395 --> 00:02:14,980
more interesting story than anything.

34
00:02:14,980 --> 00:02:19,907
I worked on an edutainment product called the Lunar Explorer, which allowed you to circle

35
00:02:19,907 --> 00:02:21,449
and land on the moon.

36
00:02:22,330 --> 00:02:24,590
using actual topographic data.

37
00:02:24,590 --> 00:02:27,691
I worked for ILM for a while, actually,

38
00:02:27,691 --> 00:02:30,772
here in San Francisco, although I was based in Los Angeles,

39
00:02:30,772 --> 00:02:34,513
but I came up here every now and then.

40
00:02:34,513 --> 00:02:37,593
And I'm currently a consultant, still a little bit working

41
00:02:37,593 --> 00:02:39,134
in the games industry.

42
00:02:39,134 --> 00:02:42,795
But we are here not to talk about that.

43
00:02:42,795 --> 00:02:49,376
We're talking about Qbert, shown here in its original thing.

44
00:02:49,376 --> 00:02:50,436
Wow.

45
00:02:50,436 --> 00:02:50,837
That's it.

46
00:02:52,761 --> 00:02:55,462
I will speak on his behalf and say he is honored.

47
00:02:55,462 --> 00:03:01,525
So the original arcade and next to it the cocktail version, which a lot of people don't

48
00:03:01,525 --> 00:03:04,146
realize there was a cocktail version.

49
00:03:04,146 --> 00:03:07,368
I don't even know how many there were.

50
00:03:07,368 --> 00:03:08,588
But let's talk a little bit about it.

51
00:03:08,588 --> 00:03:12,931
The development of the game began in the spring of 1982.

52
00:03:12,931 --> 00:03:14,631
So you know, 40 years ago.

53
00:03:16,840 --> 00:03:24,882
It ended in the fall, the production began in October, that's when they started rolling off the production line.

54
00:03:24,882 --> 00:03:30,844
And, you know, I am told, because I really didn't know, I had no interest back in the day of things like this.

55
00:03:30,844 --> 00:03:34,765
I was just amazed that the game got made at all.

56
00:03:34,765 --> 00:03:39,207
But there were about 25,000, and I'm getting that from Wikipedia, so it is suspect.

57
00:03:39,727 --> 00:03:44,148
But I have no idea how many cocktails were built.

58
00:03:44,148 --> 00:03:46,529
I do know that there are a few still floating around.

59
00:03:46,529 --> 00:03:51,511
Anyway, before we get into the actual making of Cuba,

60
00:03:51,511 --> 00:03:56,173
a little bit of back story about Gottlieb, which is

61
00:03:56,173 --> 00:03:58,033
the company that I work for.

62
00:03:58,033 --> 00:04:02,615
So Gottlieb, one of the original pinball manufacturers

63
00:04:02,615 --> 00:04:04,195
from the early 1900s.

64
00:04:06,095 --> 00:04:09,940
Gottlieb Amusement Games is what they were known as when I worked there,

65
00:04:09,940 --> 00:04:13,223
originally known as D. Gottlieb and Company.

66
00:04:13,223 --> 00:04:17,668
It was a family-owned maker of pinball machines since 1927.

67
00:04:19,739 --> 00:04:23,160
It was purchased by Columbia Pictures in 1976.

68
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:26,821
The family sold the business.

69
00:04:26,821 --> 00:04:31,362
It was also the last of the major pinball manufacturers

70
00:04:31,362 --> 00:04:33,162
to get into video games.

71
00:04:33,162 --> 00:04:37,423
I'm not sure why that is, but other companies

72
00:04:37,423 --> 00:04:40,764
like Stern and Williams, they sort of

73
00:04:40,764 --> 00:04:43,165
saw that video games were a thing.

74
00:04:43,165 --> 00:04:46,005
And I think Gottlieb held back and thought,

75
00:04:46,005 --> 00:04:49,086
ah, video games, that fad, it's not going to last.

76
00:04:51,747 --> 00:04:56,028
But eventually they realized they had to get in the business, and so they licensed two

77
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:58,629
Japanese games in the very late 1970s.

78
00:04:58,629 --> 00:05:04,571
They were called No Man's Land and New York, New York.

79
00:05:04,571 --> 00:05:07,913
Has anybody ever heard of these games?

80
00:05:07,913 --> 00:05:09,313
Oh my God.

81
00:05:09,313 --> 00:05:13,335
Well, you are special, and you know that.

82
00:05:13,335 --> 00:05:16,856
But so, other than Van.

83
00:05:18,745 --> 00:05:22,907
Nobody else has heard of these games, but it did get their feet wet and I think they

84
00:05:22,907 --> 00:05:26,889
started to realize, management started to realize, we've got to get into this, we've

85
00:05:26,889 --> 00:05:29,170
got to get into this business.

86
00:05:29,170 --> 00:05:29,931
So they decided.

87
00:05:30,933 --> 00:05:33,096
to start a video department.

88
00:05:33,096 --> 00:05:36,119
And they put two guys in charge.

89
00:05:36,119 --> 00:05:39,182
And the two guys they put in charge were Howie Rubin,

90
00:05:39,182 --> 00:05:40,623
VP of Business Development,

91
00:05:40,623 --> 00:05:42,746
and Ron Waxman, VP of Engineering.

92
00:05:42,746 --> 00:05:44,047
Here's a picture of Howie.

93
00:05:44,047 --> 00:05:45,569
This was taken actually in 2018

94
00:05:45,569 --> 00:05:48,932
at the Pinball Expo in Illinois.

95
00:05:48,932 --> 00:05:51,194
Here's a picture of Ron Waxman.

96
00:05:52,475 --> 00:05:54,296
Of course, it's not actually him.

97
00:05:54,296 --> 00:05:56,817
But I don't have a picture of Ron.

98
00:05:56,817 --> 00:06:01,699
I have never seen a picture of Ron Waxman, just adds to his mystery.

99
00:06:01,699 --> 00:06:08,801
But this picture is actually taken from a marquee in which Ron Waxman was the featured

100
00:06:08,801 --> 00:06:10,322
character, but we'll talk about that.

101
00:06:10,322 --> 00:06:15,624
Anyway, upper management at Gottlieb decided, well, we don't want to start this department

102
00:06:15,624 --> 00:06:18,665
in our plant at Northlake where they make all the pinball machines.

103
00:06:18,905 --> 00:06:24,506
much to the dismay of all the pinball designers who really thought they were going to get the chance, but they didn't.

104
00:06:24,506 --> 00:06:28,808
They opened it up in Bensonville, about eight miles away,

105
00:06:28,808 --> 00:06:32,069
and they hired somebody who had a track record in video games.

106
00:06:32,069 --> 00:06:36,910
This guy. He is Tim Skelly.

107
00:06:36,910 --> 00:06:38,031
Tim was renowned...

108
00:06:39,351 --> 00:06:45,816
Thank you. He was renowned as the designer of games like Star Castle, Rip Off, Armor Attack.

109
00:06:45,816 --> 00:06:53,182
He was the rock star guru who came and he was going to show Gottlieb how to make video games.

110
00:06:53,182 --> 00:07:00,087
He became sort of the de facto mentor to the department just because of his track record

111
00:07:00,087 --> 00:07:05,371
and the fact that nobody else really had one and had never made a game. He also would later

112
00:07:05,371 --> 00:07:07,973
give Qbert the nickname Noser.

113
00:07:09,354 --> 00:07:13,838
But for now, this is him sitting upon his game Reactor.

114
00:07:13,838 --> 00:07:17,281
So Reactor was the first game that Gottlieb produced

115
00:07:17,281 --> 00:07:20,444
in-house, designed by Tim.

116
00:07:20,444 --> 00:07:22,626
So how do I come in the picture?

117
00:07:22,626 --> 00:07:25,288
The question is how do you get a job

118
00:07:25,288 --> 00:07:26,569
making video games in 1982?

119
00:07:26,569 --> 00:07:32,295
And the answer is you look in the newspaper in the want ads.

120
00:07:33,763 --> 00:07:38,947
I'm hoping I don't have to explain to this crowd what a newspaper is.

121
00:07:38,947 --> 00:07:44,532
And I won't go into the circumstances why I was looking for a job around Christmas of

122
00:07:44,532 --> 00:07:45,773
1981, but I was.

123
00:07:45,773 --> 00:07:51,098
And in the Chicago Tribune, I came upon this—this is literally the actual ad.

124
00:07:51,098 --> 00:07:53,760
I hunted it down a couple years ago.

125
00:07:53,760 --> 00:07:56,262
Gottlieb was looking for a job.

126
00:07:56,382 --> 00:07:58,544
hardware software engineers to make video games.

127
00:07:58,544 --> 00:08:00,125
And I couldn't believe it, honestly.

128
00:08:00,125 --> 00:08:03,448
I always thought you had to be some kind of special person

129
00:08:03,448 --> 00:08:05,350
or you had to know people.

130
00:08:05,350 --> 00:08:07,392
I just couldn't believe this was right in front of me.

131
00:08:07,392 --> 00:08:10,694
So I actually sent in a cover letter and a resume

132
00:08:10,694 --> 00:08:13,196
and I got a response almost immediately.

133
00:08:13,196 --> 00:08:15,979
So this happened right around Christmas, 1981.

134
00:08:15,979 --> 00:08:18,901
I think I went in for my interview on January 2nd of 1982.

135
00:08:18,901 --> 00:08:21,964
And this is the building.

136
00:08:22,124 --> 00:08:23,164
This was the building.

137
00:08:23,164 --> 00:08:24,945
It's a, this is of course a modern photo,

138
00:08:24,945 --> 00:08:26,605
so it is no longer Gottlieb,

139
00:08:26,605 --> 00:08:29,925
but it really hasn't changed very much.

140
00:08:29,925 --> 00:08:32,766
I think it was more of a drab gray back then,

141
00:08:32,766 --> 00:08:34,606
but essentially the same building.

142
00:08:34,606 --> 00:08:37,247
As I was walking in for my interview,

143
00:08:37,247 --> 00:08:40,307
this guy was sort of coming outside.

144
00:08:40,307 --> 00:08:45,268
It was a very, like a round, large, round, rotund man

145
00:08:45,268 --> 00:08:46,828
with a very gruff voice.

146
00:08:46,828 --> 00:08:48,189
And as I'm going in, he goes,

147
00:08:48,189 --> 00:08:49,389
are you here for an interview?

148
00:08:50,189 --> 00:08:53,817
And I said, well, yeah, he goes, watch out for that waxman guy.

149
00:08:53,817 --> 00:08:54,839
He's a real asshole.

150
00:08:56,740 --> 00:09:00,401
So I took that with a grain of salt.

151
00:09:00,401 --> 00:09:03,583
I thought it was a little odd going in.

152
00:09:03,583 --> 00:09:04,843
And I was shown around.

153
00:09:04,843 --> 00:09:07,844
I was shown the department by a very lovely gentleman

154
00:09:07,844 --> 00:09:10,546
named Bill Jacobs, who was a middle manager there.

155
00:09:10,546 --> 00:09:12,706
I met the crew, met the people.

156
00:09:12,706 --> 00:09:16,808
They were working on two different games at the time.

157
00:09:16,808 --> 00:09:18,669
Other than Tim, who was working on Reactor,

158
00:09:18,669 --> 00:09:22,691
they were working on a pinball video hybrid called Caveman.

159
00:09:23,551 --> 00:09:30,236
And they were also work that had like an Apple II based game called Quizimoto.

160
00:09:30,236 --> 00:09:31,998
Caveman was released.

161
00:09:31,998 --> 00:09:35,320
It was basically a pinball machine with a video monitor embedded.

162
00:09:35,320 --> 00:09:37,702
Probably the first time that happened.

163
00:09:37,702 --> 00:09:42,606
Anyway, so I was hired.

164
00:09:42,606 --> 00:09:43,527
Oh, actually, let me tell you that.

165
00:09:43,527 --> 00:09:46,709
So when I finally got to the interview part where I had to meet Waxman.

166
00:09:48,247 --> 00:09:52,650
I go into this conference room and the guy comes in, Waxman comes in, and Waxman is the

167
00:09:52,650 --> 00:09:57,073
guy who said to me out in the parking lot, look out for that Waxman guy, he's a real

168
00:09:57,073 --> 00:09:57,393
asshole.

169
00:09:57,393 --> 00:10:01,076
So I almost forgot the punchline of the story.

170
00:10:01,076 --> 00:10:07,060
But that interview was really, it was really interesting because he was very, he's very

171
00:10:07,060 --> 00:10:11,823
gruff, like he sits there and he just, and he smokes a cigar, always had a cigar in his

172
00:10:11,823 --> 00:10:12,023
mouth.

173
00:10:12,023 --> 00:10:16,546
And he'd be saying things like, what makes you think you can design a video game?

174
00:10:18,878 --> 00:10:21,238
I don't know. I've never tried it before.

175
00:10:21,238 --> 00:10:24,519
You have a computer at home? This is 1982.

176
00:10:24,519 --> 00:10:28,960
Not a lot of people had computers at home.

177
00:10:28,960 --> 00:10:32,941
No, I use them at work, so I didn't see a need to have one at home.

178
00:10:32,941 --> 00:10:34,582
And all the questions were kind of like that.

179
00:10:34,582 --> 00:10:37,523
They sort of presupposed that I had no right to be there.

180
00:10:37,523 --> 00:10:40,143
So I left that interview thinking for sure.

181
00:10:40,904 --> 00:10:42,284
I'm not getting this job.

182
00:10:42,284 --> 00:10:45,686
So much to my surprise, I was offered a job and I took it.

183
00:10:45,686 --> 00:10:49,388
And it turned out Ron Waxman was not that gruff guy at all.

184
00:10:49,388 --> 00:10:50,529
It's just his persona.

185
00:10:50,529 --> 00:10:52,870
And I just think he did that to mess with people.

186
00:10:52,870 --> 00:10:56,813
But he was really a very warm hearted person

187
00:10:56,813 --> 00:10:58,574
once you got to know him.

188
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:00,014
Anyway, so here I am, I'm working for Gottlieb

189
00:11:00,014 --> 00:11:02,216
and we have a hardware.

190
00:11:02,216 --> 00:11:03,717
They have developed hardware.

191
00:11:03,717 --> 00:11:06,538
The engineer who developed this board

192
00:11:06,538 --> 00:11:08,299
was called, it was named Jun Yum.

193
00:11:08,299 --> 00:11:08,359
And.

194
00:11:11,110 --> 00:11:13,352
This was our major board.

195
00:11:13,352 --> 00:11:16,114
It had, well let me go through the specs of it.

196
00:11:16,114 --> 00:11:21,417
So it was based on an Intel 8088 CPU,

197
00:11:21,417 --> 00:11:24,539
64 kilobytes of program memory.

198
00:11:24,539 --> 00:11:25,560
Now you gotta realize,

199
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:29,803
we programmed everything in assembler.

200
00:11:29,803 --> 00:11:31,884
So we had to make things tight,

201
00:11:31,884 --> 00:11:33,906
but still, everything was assembler,

202
00:11:33,906 --> 00:11:35,567
was pretty tight anyway.

203
00:11:35,567 --> 00:11:37,548
So 64 kilobytes, pretty standard at the time.

204
00:11:38,484 --> 00:11:41,226
screen resolution of 256 by 240 pixels.

205
00:11:41,226 --> 00:11:44,930
We had 64 foreground sprites

206
00:11:44,930 --> 00:11:49,735
and a sprite was 16 by 16 pixels.

207
00:11:49,735 --> 00:11:54,100
The hardware took care of the display.

208
00:11:54,100 --> 00:11:56,703
So as a programmer, it was very easy to put up,

209
00:11:56,703 --> 00:11:58,985
you know, you had sprites in your memory,

210
00:11:58,985 --> 00:12:00,207
they were indexed, so you just...

211
00:12:00,947 --> 00:12:04,834
wrote into a foreground registry this index

212
00:12:04,834 --> 00:12:07,998
at this x and this y, and the hardware just put it there.

213
00:12:07,998 --> 00:12:09,260
Very easy to write code for it.

214
00:12:09,260 --> 00:12:14,449
The background was basically eight by eight pixel blocks.

215
00:12:16,259 --> 00:12:19,801
So you had 32 by 30 blocks to fill the background,

216
00:12:19,801 --> 00:12:21,361
and a 16 color palette.

217
00:12:21,361 --> 00:12:25,002
So you had 16 colors and each of those colors

218
00:12:25,002 --> 00:12:27,583
could be one of 32,768, which is basically

219
00:12:27,583 --> 00:12:32,185
five bits of red, green, and blue, 15-bit color.

220
00:12:33,646 --> 00:12:35,966
And again, I think that was pretty standard

221
00:12:35,966 --> 00:12:39,207
for the arcade industry at the time.

222
00:12:39,207 --> 00:12:42,248
As far as coding, for programmers out there,

223
00:12:42,248 --> 00:12:44,049
there was no operating system really.

224
00:12:44,049 --> 00:12:46,130
We had a main loop, that was it.

225
00:12:46,130 --> 00:12:48,971
So you did everything you needed to do

226
00:12:48,971 --> 00:12:51,552
that you wanted to get done in a 60th of a second,

227
00:12:51,552 --> 00:12:53,512
and then you called a V blank wait.

228
00:12:53,512 --> 00:12:55,993
So you just waited for the screen to refresh.

229
00:12:55,993 --> 00:12:58,254
If you could get all of that in there.

230
00:12:58,254 --> 00:12:59,954
If you had too much going on,

231
00:13:00,815 --> 00:13:02,937
the screen missed the V blank

232
00:13:02,937 --> 00:13:05,359
and you had to wait till the next frame,

233
00:13:05,359 --> 00:13:05,860
which you didn't want.

234
00:13:05,860 --> 00:13:06,421
Anyway.

235
00:13:08,472 --> 00:13:12,815
So the same pinball soundboard was used for our video games,

236
00:13:12,815 --> 00:13:15,157
and we'll talk a little bit more about that later.

237
00:13:15,157 --> 00:13:16,918
Had dip switches on the board.

238
00:13:16,918 --> 00:13:19,260
The dip switch is used for things like free play,

239
00:13:19,260 --> 00:13:20,822
on and off.

240
00:13:20,822 --> 00:13:23,103
Cocktail, remember I was talking about the cocktail table?

241
00:13:23,103 --> 00:13:24,765
The cocktail table was interesting.

242
00:13:24,765 --> 00:13:27,267
Players sit head to head, so between turns,

243
00:13:27,267 --> 00:13:30,049
the screen has to flip vertically.

244
00:13:30,049 --> 00:13:31,750
So that was a dip switch setting.

245
00:13:31,750 --> 00:13:36,614
The track mode had sound, but you could turn it off.

246
00:13:36,614 --> 00:13:37,695
A lot of operators.

247
00:13:38,096 --> 00:13:40,821
They didn't want the attract mode making noise

248
00:13:40,821 --> 00:13:43,686
for whatever reason, so that was a dip switch.

249
00:13:43,686 --> 00:13:47,914
And in Qbert later on, the knocker was put on a dip switch.

250
00:13:47,914 --> 00:13:47,954
So.

251
00:13:48,850 --> 00:13:49,851
Operators can turn that off.

252
00:13:49,851 --> 00:13:54,937
But what did we use as a development system?

253
00:13:54,937 --> 00:13:56,538
Oh, wait, dip switch.

254
00:13:56,538 --> 00:13:58,540
Oh yeah, I wanted to talk about the foreground

255
00:13:58,540 --> 00:13:59,521
and background switching.

256
00:13:59,521 --> 00:14:02,845
So there was a mechanism in the hardware

257
00:14:02,845 --> 00:14:05,027
that if you set a bit on a certain memory location,

258
00:14:05,027 --> 00:14:08,891
it would flip the foreground and background.

259
00:14:08,891 --> 00:14:10,312
Why, you ask?

260
00:14:10,312 --> 00:14:11,834
What use could this possibly be?

261
00:14:12,922 --> 00:14:15,503
We didn't know, they put it in there,

262
00:14:15,503 --> 00:14:18,826
and we tried to see if we could make use of it.

263
00:14:18,826 --> 00:14:20,167
And as it turned out, we did.

264
00:14:20,167 --> 00:14:23,729
And then finally, what did that say?

265
00:14:23,729 --> 00:14:25,771
Oh, upside down, yeah, upside down, that was cocktail.

266
00:14:25,771 --> 00:14:27,512
That's how we did the cocktail.

267
00:14:27,512 --> 00:14:29,713
Enabled on the...

268
00:14:30,922 --> 00:14:33,503
dip switch, and then programmed in software.

269
00:14:33,503 --> 00:14:36,504
So, this was our development system.

270
00:14:36,504 --> 00:14:38,665
It was called an MDS-80.

271
00:14:38,665 --> 00:14:43,007
We called it the blue box, I think, for obvious reasons.

272
00:14:43,007 --> 00:14:45,468
It was based on an in-circuit emulator,

273
00:14:45,468 --> 00:14:48,450
so there was a ribbon cable that came out,

274
00:14:48,450 --> 00:14:51,471
and the socket plugged into our board

275
00:14:51,471 --> 00:14:53,252
where the processor would normally go.

276
00:14:54,092 --> 00:14:56,173
And that's what we would use.

277
00:14:56,173 --> 00:14:58,134
And we had three of those when I started.

278
00:14:58,134 --> 00:14:59,574
So we didn't have a lot of people.

279
00:14:59,574 --> 00:15:04,736
It was a small team, maybe, I want to say like 12 people,

280
00:15:04,736 --> 00:15:08,218
actually, you know, hardware engineers, sound artists,

281
00:15:08,218 --> 00:15:10,999
not a lot of people.

282
00:15:10,999 --> 00:15:12,399
And we only had three of these to share.

283
00:15:13,949 --> 00:15:20,653
at first. We did have some art tools that had been programmed and basically they were

284
00:15:20,653 --> 00:15:25,656
so simple it was like a grid, like for foreground you'd have a 16 by 16 grid, you'd have a palette,

285
00:15:25,656 --> 00:15:31,941
you could pick your colors and then literally plop squares in the grid. And that's how artists

286
00:15:31,941 --> 00:15:38,545
would create the art. They were called Fogus for foreground and Bogus for background.

287
00:15:39,185 --> 00:15:41,927
I did not name them.

288
00:15:41,927 --> 00:15:43,027
So what was I doing?

289
00:15:43,027 --> 00:15:45,408
So basically, they said to me when I was hired,

290
00:15:45,408 --> 00:15:47,229
you got to learn the system.

291
00:15:47,229 --> 00:15:49,950
And we got a guy who's making a game.

292
00:15:49,950 --> 00:15:51,190
His name was Tom Malinowski.

293
00:15:51,190 --> 00:15:54,272
He was making a superhero game.

294
00:15:54,272 --> 00:15:58,414
And they asked me to help him out, sort of learn the ropes,

295
00:15:58,414 --> 00:16:00,514
get my feet wet, which I did.

296
00:16:00,514 --> 00:16:02,175
In this particular, so basically,

297
00:16:02,175 --> 00:16:04,736
it's a game based on Superman.

298
00:16:05,917 --> 00:16:10,282
Superman 2, Superman battling the three Kryptonian villains.

299
00:16:10,282 --> 00:16:11,463
Of course, we didn't get the license for that

300
00:16:11,463 --> 00:16:12,744
because that would cost money.

301
00:16:12,744 --> 00:16:14,907
So it was just some generic superhero.

302
00:16:14,907 --> 00:16:19,792
My contribution here was that you could knock the villains

303
00:16:19,792 --> 00:16:22,815
into the buildings and some rubble would spew out

304
00:16:22,815 --> 00:16:24,737
and land on the ground.

305
00:16:24,737 --> 00:16:26,219
So I programmed the rubble.

306
00:16:26,989 --> 00:16:28,830
And then when the rubble accumulated,

307
00:16:28,830 --> 00:16:30,570
we needed a way to get rid of it,

308
00:16:30,570 --> 00:16:36,051
so I programmed the bulldozer at the bottom of the screen.

309
00:16:36,051 --> 00:16:37,692
Anyway, I mean, I had to do something.

310
00:16:37,692 --> 00:16:40,892
But the funny thing about this game, it was never released.

311
00:16:40,892 --> 00:16:45,373
It went through many iterations, went through many names.

312
00:16:45,373 --> 00:16:47,794
For some reason, every time they changed something on it,

313
00:16:47,794 --> 00:16:49,474
they put it out on test with a different name.

314
00:16:49,474 --> 00:16:52,315
So it was Protector, it was Video Man,

315
00:16:52,315 --> 00:16:53,755
then it was Guardian.

316
00:16:53,755 --> 00:16:56,756
Inexplicably to me, then, the fourth one was Argus.

317
00:16:57,837 --> 00:17:00,279
And it just kept going out and not testing well.

318
00:17:00,279 --> 00:17:03,682
And so for me, I just started calling it ProVidGuard Argus,

319
00:17:03,682 --> 00:17:05,744
and to this day, that's what I call it.

320
00:17:05,744 --> 00:17:07,545
But ironically, they released it.

321
00:17:07,545 --> 00:17:10,428
Jeff Lee, the artist, and Tom Alanowski

322
00:17:10,428 --> 00:17:12,530
found some old ROMs, and a couple years ago,

323
00:17:12,530 --> 00:17:14,892
they actually released it.

324
00:17:14,892 --> 00:17:17,574
So you can play this game in an arcade cabinet

325
00:17:17,574 --> 00:17:19,476
at the Galloping Ghost in Illinois.

326
00:17:21,138 --> 00:17:24,602
Oh, and then the other name I forgot to mention was Waxman,

327
00:17:24,602 --> 00:17:27,826
because at one point they decided to replace

328
00:17:27,826 --> 00:17:31,090
the main character with a version of Ron Waxman.

329
00:17:31,090 --> 00:17:34,134
And I'm not joking, that actually happened.

330
00:17:34,134 --> 00:17:35,716
But it still did not test well.

331
00:17:37,797 --> 00:17:38,778
All right, so now what?

332
00:17:38,778 --> 00:17:42,022
I got my feet wet, I know the system.

333
00:17:42,022 --> 00:17:44,826
Basically, management, and when I say management,

334
00:17:44,826 --> 00:17:48,271
I mean Ron and Howie said to me, make a game.

335
00:17:48,271 --> 00:17:50,013
That was literally all I was told.

336
00:17:52,495 --> 00:17:55,217
All right, well, I was walking down the office one day.

337
00:17:55,217 --> 00:17:56,638
We had a big open area.

338
00:17:56,638 --> 00:17:58,499
We didn't have individual offices.

339
00:17:58,499 --> 00:18:02,402
We had just work tables and a big room.

340
00:18:02,402 --> 00:18:05,084
And like I said, we shared those blue boxes

341
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:06,385
that we only had three of.

342
00:18:06,385 --> 00:18:09,988
And I was walking by, and this one programmer

343
00:18:09,988 --> 00:18:12,830
named Kanyabamoto, who is pretty much known

344
00:18:12,830 --> 00:18:15,112
for his game Mad Planets, if you've ever heard of that.

345
00:18:15,512 --> 00:18:21,834
But Kahn was working, he was actually playing with that foreground background switching bit.

346
00:18:21,834 --> 00:18:26,196
He just, he had a background image that looked like this.

347
00:18:26,196 --> 00:18:32,097
So Jeff Lee created, I think it was literally six background blocks that you could repeat

348
00:18:32,097 --> 00:18:34,318
and fill the screen to make this thing.

349
00:18:34,318 --> 00:18:39,120
And I was walking by and Kahn, this of course is background, but Kahn was using it.

350
00:18:39,320 --> 00:18:42,242
as a foreground and then removing blocks

351
00:18:42,242 --> 00:18:43,643
to reveal the background,

352
00:18:43,643 --> 00:18:46,064
or reveal the foreground behind it,

353
00:18:46,064 --> 00:18:47,585
to what purpose, I don't know.

354
00:18:47,585 --> 00:18:50,107
But I saw it and I just thought to myself,

355
00:18:50,107 --> 00:18:53,149
this is interesting because if something fell

356
00:18:53,149 --> 00:18:54,470
on a cube, on a single cube,

357
00:18:54,470 --> 00:18:57,292
it would have one of two ways to bounce, right?

358
00:18:57,292 --> 00:18:59,874
It would bounce down to the right, down to the left.

359
00:18:59,874 --> 00:19:02,636
And that's binary, zero or one.

360
00:19:03,376 --> 00:19:07,758
And with seven rows of those cubes,

361
00:19:07,758 --> 00:19:10,560
which is what could fit on one of our screens,

362
00:19:10,560 --> 00:19:14,963
you could put the entire path of a ball in one byte.

363
00:19:15,675 --> 00:19:18,316
So that's what occurred to me.

364
00:19:18,316 --> 00:19:24,120
So I set about taking that full screen, shaping it like this.

365
00:19:24,120 --> 00:19:26,742
And then I went to Jeff, and I asked him for a ball,

366
00:19:26,742 --> 00:19:27,642
a bouncing ball.

367
00:19:27,642 --> 00:19:30,384
So basically, all I was looking to do

368
00:19:30,384 --> 00:19:33,206
was program randomness and gravity,

369
00:19:33,206 --> 00:19:34,647
is to learn how to do that.

370
00:19:34,647 --> 00:19:38,309
The rubble in the previous game had no gravity.

371
00:19:38,309 --> 00:19:40,731
If it fell, it just fell at a linear rate,

372
00:19:40,731 --> 00:19:42,632
which was very bizarre.

373
00:19:42,632 --> 00:19:42,792
But.

374
00:19:42,972 --> 00:19:45,715
I didn't know how to do gravity at the time.

375
00:19:45,715 --> 00:19:46,997
It was not too hard.

376
00:19:46,997 --> 00:19:49,719
But anyway, so it was just a programming exercise.

377
00:19:49,719 --> 00:19:51,141
That's literally all it was.

378
00:19:51,141 --> 00:19:56,607
Well, you know, once you've got that, then, you know, the question is, what do you want

379
00:19:56,607 --> 00:19:57,948
to do next?

380
00:19:57,948 --> 00:20:00,251
And it occurred to me...

381
00:20:01,751 --> 00:20:04,393
Oh, I should mention also, and I'll show you this later,

382
00:20:04,393 --> 00:20:05,814
but the random number generator I used,

383
00:20:05,814 --> 00:20:08,477
I got from Tim Skelly, but we'll talk about that in a minute.

384
00:20:08,477 --> 00:20:11,679
The third thing, obviously, well, if this is working

385
00:20:11,679 --> 00:20:13,140
and people are looking at it and they're saying,

386
00:20:13,140 --> 00:20:16,503
this is pretty cool, the ball's bouncing down,

387
00:20:16,503 --> 00:20:18,045
maybe I should have a player character

388
00:20:18,045 --> 00:20:20,186
that jumps all over the screen.

389
00:20:20,186 --> 00:20:22,008
So that was my next thing.

390
00:20:22,008 --> 00:20:24,850
So I went to Jeff, I said, do you have some art,

391
00:20:24,850 --> 00:20:25,771
some character I can use?

392
00:20:25,771 --> 00:20:28,533
And he put a bunch of characters up on the screen

393
00:20:28,533 --> 00:20:29,694
on his development system.

394
00:20:31,076 --> 00:20:35,563
I think they were pretty much the characters that ultimately went into Q-Bert,

395
00:20:35,563 --> 00:20:38,548
but they just were random characters at the time.

396
00:20:38,548 --> 00:20:42,695
And I saw this round one, long nose, looked kind of pathetic.

397
00:20:43,753 --> 00:20:45,834
And I thought, that's the one I want.

398
00:20:45,834 --> 00:20:49,517
So I asked him to give me all the angles I needed,

399
00:20:49,517 --> 00:20:51,819
looking up, looking down, jumping, and all that stuff.

400
00:20:51,819 --> 00:20:53,180
And he gave me that.

401
00:20:53,180 --> 00:20:57,143
So the next thing was, I had a player character

402
00:20:57,143 --> 00:20:58,945
jumping around the pyramid.

403
00:20:58,945 --> 00:21:01,547
Now, Jeff designed that character with a long nose

404
00:21:01,547 --> 00:21:05,630
because his intention was he would shoot stuff out

405
00:21:05,630 --> 00:21:05,930
of his nose.

406
00:21:06,678 --> 00:21:08,499
But that was way too complicated.

407
00:21:08,499 --> 00:21:09,779
This is my first game.

408
00:21:09,779 --> 00:21:10,960
I really wasn't interested in that.

409
00:21:10,960 --> 00:21:13,540
So I sort of nixed that idea, and I was just like,

410
00:21:13,540 --> 00:21:16,001
let me just get the guy jumping.

411
00:21:16,001 --> 00:21:16,281
So I did.

412
00:21:16,281 --> 00:21:23,883
After that, things just started happening just naturally,

413
00:21:23,883 --> 00:21:24,443
I want to say.

414
00:21:24,443 --> 00:21:28,344
I've always said that the design of Q-Bert

415
00:21:28,344 --> 00:21:31,365
was evolutionary in that.

416
00:21:32,038 --> 00:21:35,020
I programmed something, and then I sort of decided,

417
00:21:35,020 --> 00:21:36,942
what do I want to program next?

418
00:21:36,942 --> 00:21:39,323
Nothing was really thought about in advance.

419
00:21:39,323 --> 00:21:41,805
Everything happened one step at a time.

420
00:21:41,805 --> 00:21:43,085
So, you know, I thought, okay,

421
00:21:43,085 --> 00:21:44,646
well, the player's jumping around the pyramid,

422
00:21:44,646 --> 00:21:47,988
there are balls, he needs to collide with the balls.

423
00:21:47,988 --> 00:21:49,649
The balls need to be dangerous, you know?

424
00:21:50,270 --> 00:21:55,833
And then the whole thing about having him fall off, that was a little bit of a controversial issue.

425
00:21:55,833 --> 00:22:00,937
It seemed natural to me that the player should avoid jumping off the pyramid.

426
00:22:00,937 --> 00:22:03,178
Some people said, no, it makes it too hard.

427
00:22:03,178 --> 00:22:04,799
And I sort of stuck to my guns on that.

428
00:22:04,799 --> 00:22:08,201
But the nice thing about the jumping off the pyramid, I don't know if you've ever noticed this,

429
00:22:08,201 --> 00:22:12,844
but what happens when he jumps off the pyramid is I use that bit and I switch the foreground

430
00:22:12,844 --> 00:22:16,606
and background so he actually falls behind the pyramid.

431
00:22:16,606 --> 00:22:19,348
And yay, that thing was of use.

432
00:22:20,467 --> 00:22:25,813
Um, okay, so, it's still not a game though.

433
00:22:25,813 --> 00:22:30,097
It's just, you know, it's a guy jumping around a pyramid and balls.

434
00:22:30,097 --> 00:22:32,640
He's trying to avoid balls.

435
00:22:32,640 --> 00:22:36,845
So one night, I'm working late and I'm just sort of having jumping around, just

436
00:22:36,845 --> 00:22:40,109
looking for some kind of inspiration or think of what I might want to do next.

437
00:22:40,709 --> 00:22:49,016
And Waxman had this habit of sitting like in the room, in our workroom while we were working.

438
00:22:49,016 --> 00:22:52,099
And sometimes he'd like sit behind you.

439
00:22:52,099 --> 00:22:56,563
And it was very unnerving because, you know, you're there, you're working, you're trying to do whatever you're trying to do.

440
00:22:56,563 --> 00:22:58,624
He's just sitting behind you smoking his cigar.

441
00:22:58,624 --> 00:23:05,971
You know, you can hear him breathing like Darth Vader or somebody.

442
00:23:05,971 --> 00:23:06,131
And.

443
00:23:07,227 --> 00:23:10,069
I'm jumping around, just sort of playing the game, and out of nowhere he just says,

444
00:23:10,069 --> 00:23:14,953
uh, what if the cubes change color when he lands on them?

445
00:23:14,953 --> 00:23:19,557
I thought, yeah!

446
00:23:21,325 --> 00:23:23,166
That's a great idea.

447
00:23:23,166 --> 00:23:25,146
And I will say this about Qbert.

448
00:23:25,146 --> 00:23:26,587
It was my first game.

449
00:23:26,587 --> 00:23:30,707
I was not so arrogant as to think I had all the answers.

450
00:23:30,707 --> 00:23:33,268
I was happy to listen to anybody's suggestions.

451
00:23:33,268 --> 00:23:36,589
And believe me, people gave me a lot of suggestions

452
00:23:36,589 --> 00:23:37,409
that I did not take.

453
00:23:37,409 --> 00:23:39,770
But I was the one who had to implement them.

454
00:23:39,770 --> 00:23:41,730
So if somebody gave me a suggestion

455
00:23:41,730 --> 00:23:44,411
and it sounded right, I was like, awesome.

456
00:23:44,411 --> 00:23:48,211
So that was a great suggestion.

457
00:23:48,211 --> 00:23:48,752
I took it.

458
00:23:48,932 --> 00:23:51,873
That's when it became a game.

459
00:23:51,873 --> 00:23:56,334
And honestly, the rest of it sort of happened fairly quickly.

460
00:23:56,334 --> 00:23:59,476
In fact, there's a story that Howie Rubin likes to tell,

461
00:23:59,476 --> 00:24:03,117
where he didn't know anything about what was going on.

462
00:24:03,117 --> 00:24:05,838
And he went to Japan for a business trip.

463
00:24:05,838 --> 00:24:08,019
He came back two weeks later, and the game

464
00:24:08,019 --> 00:24:08,799
was completely done.

465
00:24:08,799 --> 00:24:10,920
In his mind, that's what happens.

466
00:24:10,920 --> 00:24:13,121
Like, it didn't exist, and then two weeks later,

467
00:24:13,121 --> 00:24:13,901
it was completely done.

468
00:24:14,321 --> 00:24:15,162
Not quite true.

469
00:24:15,162 --> 00:24:19,985
But anyway, my goal, because it was my first game,

470
00:24:19,985 --> 00:24:22,186
was to keep it simple.

471
00:24:22,186 --> 00:24:26,329
But all of these things happened pretty much in succession.

472
00:24:26,329 --> 00:24:28,631
So we need a bad guy.

473
00:24:28,631 --> 00:24:31,473
We need somebody to chase him.

474
00:24:31,473 --> 00:24:34,795
He needs a way to jump off the pyramid and not die.

475
00:24:34,795 --> 00:24:38,978
Slick and Sam, these characters fall down and just

476
00:24:38,978 --> 00:24:40,959
thwart his goal.

477
00:24:40,959 --> 00:24:42,720
That just seemed, again, like a pretty obvious thing.

478
00:24:43,806 --> 00:24:48,108
Ugg and wrong way, okay, these guys come up with a different axis of gravity.

479
00:24:48,108 --> 00:24:51,570
This was Jeff Lee's idea, and I hated it.

480
00:24:51,570 --> 00:24:57,153
And I hated it because I couldn't figure out how to do it.

481
00:24:57,153 --> 00:24:59,734
And I said, no, I can't, it's too hard.

482
00:24:59,734 --> 00:25:02,636
Remember that we're in an environment where

483
00:25:04,632 --> 00:25:08,554
Speed is important, tightness of code is important,

484
00:25:08,554 --> 00:25:11,817
it's all in assembler, we have no floating point arithmetic,

485
00:25:11,817 --> 00:25:14,358
it's all integer arithmetic.

486
00:25:14,358 --> 00:25:16,140
I didn't know how I was gonna do that.

487
00:25:16,140 --> 00:25:19,562
And I said no, and then it just nodded me

488
00:25:19,562 --> 00:25:22,144
for like days and days and days.

489
00:25:22,144 --> 00:25:24,325
And eventually I figured it out.

490
00:25:24,325 --> 00:25:26,286
I just, it like came to me and I thought,

491
00:25:26,286 --> 00:25:28,168
wait a minute, I think I can do that.

492
00:25:28,168 --> 00:25:29,589
So, Ugg and Wrongway got in the game.

493
00:25:30,489 --> 00:25:33,210
And of course, the green ball is another feature.

494
00:25:33,210 --> 00:25:37,571
It was an interesting dynamic of the way we worked together.

495
00:25:37,571 --> 00:25:41,792
Jeff was the only artist working on the game.

496
00:25:41,792 --> 00:25:45,973
He was my constant sounding board.

497
00:25:45,973 --> 00:25:48,954
He contributed so many ideas.

498
00:25:48,954 --> 00:25:51,154
I consider him a co-creator.

499
00:25:51,154 --> 00:25:53,655
It was my responsibility to make the game.

500
00:25:53,655 --> 00:25:55,335
That was just the way Gottlieb worked.

501
00:25:55,335 --> 00:25:58,556
So at Gottlieb, the programmers were considered the designers.

502
00:25:59,136 --> 00:26:00,457
because they programmed it.

503
00:26:00,457 --> 00:26:03,658
And if they didn't program something, it didn't go in.

504
00:26:03,658 --> 00:26:09,221
But Jeff was incredibly valuable and had fantastic ideas.

505
00:26:09,221 --> 00:26:10,721
And we were very simpatico.

506
00:26:10,721 --> 00:26:12,202
We sort of had the same sensibilities.

507
00:26:14,425 --> 00:26:17,106
Anyway, programming concerns.

508
00:26:17,106 --> 00:26:21,187
So there were some programming concerns going into this.

509
00:26:21,187 --> 00:26:23,748
And the first one is memory limitation.

510
00:26:23,748 --> 00:26:26,769
I said we only had 64 kilobytes of program memory,

511
00:26:26,769 --> 00:26:29,070
but this really wasn't a problem

512
00:26:29,070 --> 00:26:31,911
because I didn't find myself bloating my code.

513
00:26:31,911 --> 00:26:34,932
I was a pretty good type programmer anyway,

514
00:26:34,932 --> 00:26:38,273
so that was something I had to be cautious about,

515
00:26:38,273 --> 00:26:40,073
but it didn't really become a problem.

516
00:26:40,534 --> 00:26:42,415
But speed, that was a problem.

517
00:26:42,415 --> 00:26:45,096
We really couldn't do, even things like square root.

518
00:26:45,096 --> 00:26:49,699
So let's talk about collision detection a little bit.

519
00:26:49,699 --> 00:26:52,721
Well, first let's talk about random number generation.

520
00:26:52,721 --> 00:26:55,523
This is a sample to talk about cycle counting,

521
00:26:55,523 --> 00:26:57,604
because that's something we used to do.

522
00:26:57,604 --> 00:27:01,047
We knew how many cycles, machine cycles,

523
00:27:01,047 --> 00:27:02,448
every instruction would take.

524
00:27:03,008 --> 00:27:05,810
And so, when we made a loop or something,

525
00:27:05,810 --> 00:27:08,732
or we had any routine, we had to literally count the cycles

526
00:27:08,732 --> 00:27:11,354
to make sure it was as small and tight

527
00:27:11,354 --> 00:27:12,435
as it could possibly be.

528
00:27:12,435 --> 00:27:14,557
So this is a random number generator,

529
00:27:14,557 --> 00:27:16,118
and basically what's happening is,

530
00:27:16,118 --> 00:27:18,760
you're taking a seed, actually pseudo-random,

531
00:27:18,760 --> 00:27:22,342
you're taking a seed, you are doing some shifts,

532
00:27:22,342 --> 00:27:25,665
and whether you're shifting a bit around,

533
00:27:25,665 --> 00:27:27,046
but whether it's a one or a zero

534
00:27:27,046 --> 00:27:29,128
depends on what a couple of other bits are

535
00:27:29,128 --> 00:27:30,589
when you XOR them together.

536
00:27:32,015 --> 00:27:33,436
I think, I don't remember.

537
00:27:33,436 --> 00:27:36,378
Anyway, but it was a really interesting thing,

538
00:27:36,378 --> 00:27:38,319
and I got this from Tim Skelly.

539
00:27:38,319 --> 00:27:40,560
Tim was, I can't say enough about Tim.

540
00:27:40,560 --> 00:27:43,022
He was just the most generous guy.

541
00:27:43,022 --> 00:27:46,924
It wasn't his job to be our mentor at all.

542
00:27:46,924 --> 00:27:49,766
He was job to make a game, but he did.

543
00:27:49,766 --> 00:27:52,308
He was just very kind and generous with all of us.

544
00:27:54,837 --> 00:27:58,202
Yeah, so then the other thing, the other concern, I guess,

545
00:27:58,202 --> 00:27:59,083
collision detection.

546
00:27:59,083 --> 00:28:00,625
It's not obvious how you're going

547
00:28:00,625 --> 00:28:05,691
to make these things collide, because it is a pseudo 3D space.

548
00:28:05,691 --> 00:28:08,816
But in reality, it is a 2D space.

549
00:28:08,816 --> 00:28:12,100
So you've got a ball, and you've got Qbert.

550
00:28:12,640 --> 00:28:16,742
And they really, you know, they're just 2D sprites.

551
00:28:16,742 --> 00:28:20,764
Now, our hardware did have a sort of a Z component,

552
00:28:20,764 --> 00:28:24,165
so based on which register a foreground image was in,

553
00:28:24,165 --> 00:28:27,586
it would appear on top of or behind another image.

554
00:28:28,247 --> 00:28:32,888
But in order to really do the collision detection,

555
00:28:32,888 --> 00:28:35,929
right now, the simplest thing and the fastest thing

556
00:28:35,929 --> 00:28:37,609
is you just do a distance check.

557
00:28:37,609 --> 00:28:39,070
And you don't even do the square root.

558
00:28:39,070 --> 00:28:41,630
You just do x squared plus y squared.

559
00:28:41,630 --> 00:28:44,271
And you figure out r squared,

560
00:28:44,271 --> 00:28:45,911
how close they can be without colliding.

561
00:28:45,911 --> 00:28:49,172
But what I figured out to do in this case was

562
00:28:49,172 --> 00:28:50,373
I had to take into account

563
00:28:50,793 --> 00:28:54,195
the velocity that they were moving at, if they were moving.

564
00:28:54,195 --> 00:28:58,417
So, for example, if the ball, the ball would jump up and down.

565
00:28:58,417 --> 00:29:02,499
So based on whether it was going up, if it was going up and Q-Bert was going up, even

566
00:29:02,499 --> 00:29:04,660
if they overlapped, it wasn't a collision.

567
00:29:04,660 --> 00:29:10,143
So that's the kind of thing, you know, if they were coming at each other, yes, that

568
00:29:10,143 --> 00:29:11,863
would be a collision.

569
00:29:11,863 --> 00:29:13,064
You get the idea.

570
00:29:13,064 --> 00:29:15,625
So that was really a challenge to work out.

571
00:29:17,285 --> 00:29:19,647
When UG and wrong way came into the picture,

572
00:29:19,647 --> 00:29:21,629
that was even more of a challenge to make it,

573
00:29:21,629 --> 00:29:24,091
you know, it's really important to make it seem fair.

574
00:29:24,091 --> 00:29:26,173
You don't want these collisions to feel unfair.

575
00:29:26,173 --> 00:29:27,775
That would be extremely bad.

576
00:29:27,775 --> 00:29:32,919
And I haven't looked at the code in years

577
00:29:32,919 --> 00:29:35,561
to see what I did to handle the UG and wrong way problem

578
00:29:35,561 --> 00:29:37,223
because I'm afraid to.

579
00:29:38,312 --> 00:29:41,932
So, in the middle, so here we are in Bensonville,

580
00:29:41,932 --> 00:29:45,113
and by the way, Bensonville has a manufacturing plant.

581
00:29:45,113 --> 00:29:46,793
It's a massive manufacturing plant,

582
00:29:46,793 --> 00:29:48,694
which has been completely empty,

583
00:29:48,694 --> 00:29:51,955
because until they started making reactor,

584
00:29:51,955 --> 00:29:53,815
which was months after I got hired,

585
00:29:53,815 --> 00:29:56,476
there was nothing to produce.

586
00:29:56,476 --> 00:29:58,256
So we had a huge empty plant.

587
00:29:58,256 --> 00:30:00,276
In the middle of the day,

588
00:30:00,276 --> 00:30:01,937
Howie Rubin would come into the offices

589
00:30:01,937 --> 00:30:03,957
and go, everybody, stop working.

590
00:30:03,957 --> 00:30:05,638
We're going into the plant to play football.

591
00:30:06,398 --> 00:30:10,499
And we had to stop working and go in the plant and pay for it.

592
00:30:10,499 --> 00:30:12,419
And we wanted to work.

593
00:30:12,419 --> 00:30:14,199
We were not football players.

594
00:30:14,199 --> 00:30:17,320
But for some reason, upper management

595
00:30:17,320 --> 00:30:21,161
decided about halfway through the development of Qbert

596
00:30:21,161 --> 00:30:23,941
that they wanted to move the video department

597
00:30:23,941 --> 00:30:27,402
into the main plant in North Lake, Illinois.

598
00:30:27,402 --> 00:30:32,003
And they kind of botched it because they didn't

599
00:30:32,163 --> 00:30:34,825
they didn't get us together, there was no mixer,

600
00:30:34,825 --> 00:30:36,326
there were no introductions.

601
00:30:36,326 --> 00:30:40,469
Literally one day we just showed up at this new place

602
00:30:40,469 --> 00:30:43,451
and we had a beautiful big area,

603
00:30:43,451 --> 00:30:45,292
we all had our own cubicles,

604
00:30:45,292 --> 00:30:48,254
some people had offices around the rim

605
00:30:48,254 --> 00:30:50,036
and then we loved pinball

606
00:30:50,036 --> 00:30:52,878
and we thought the pinball guys were amazing.

607
00:30:52,878 --> 00:30:56,120
The designers, we admired them tremendously

608
00:30:56,120 --> 00:30:58,782
but they did not admire us.

609
00:30:59,322 --> 00:31:03,384
So we came to work one day and got all these stink eye.

610
00:31:03,384 --> 00:31:05,425
It's like, why those guys?

611
00:31:05,425 --> 00:31:08,026
Why do they hate us?

612
00:31:08,026 --> 00:31:11,808
Anyway, but we did move in, and we had offices

613
00:31:11,808 --> 00:31:12,769
at the main plant.

614
00:31:12,769 --> 00:31:16,010
And this thing here is the only picture

615
00:31:16,010 --> 00:31:18,291
that I have from those days.

616
00:31:18,291 --> 00:31:20,733
And I will say this.

617
00:31:20,733 --> 00:31:23,214
I don't think any of us thought what we were doing.

618
00:31:24,275 --> 00:31:25,175
meant anything.

619
00:31:25,175 --> 00:31:30,018
We thought what we were making was disposable entertainment.

620
00:31:30,018 --> 00:31:32,539
Six months later, it'd be off to the next game.

621
00:31:32,539 --> 00:31:34,420
People would forget this game.

622
00:31:34,420 --> 00:31:37,222
So I did not document anything I did

623
00:31:37,222 --> 00:31:39,063
because I just didn't see the importance of it.

624
00:31:39,063 --> 00:31:44,506
But this is the only photograph that I have of myself

625
00:31:44,506 --> 00:31:45,447
while I was developing Kubrick.

626
00:31:45,447 --> 00:31:47,348
So interesting things to say.

627
00:31:47,348 --> 00:31:50,029
Here's the blue, but you can see the blue box there

628
00:31:50,029 --> 00:31:50,669
behind me.

629
00:31:52,011 --> 00:31:54,915
ribbon cable, the hardware's just sitting out.

630
00:31:54,915 --> 00:31:56,537
This thing is interesting here.

631
00:31:56,537 --> 00:32:00,403
This is a Tupperware bucket that is upside down.

632
00:32:01,324 --> 00:32:03,725
with a joystick mounted on it.

633
00:32:03,725 --> 00:32:07,127
And I can't stress the amount of grief I got

634
00:32:07,127 --> 00:32:08,088
for that joystick.

635
00:32:08,088 --> 00:32:10,609
Now, I mean, if you look at the play field,

636
00:32:10,609 --> 00:32:12,610
it seems absolutely obvious to me

637
00:32:12,610 --> 00:32:15,371
that you only have four possible directions to go

638
00:32:15,371 --> 00:32:16,552
and they are diagonal.

639
00:32:16,552 --> 00:32:21,474
But people would walk up and straighten out that bucket

640
00:32:21,474 --> 00:32:23,035
so that it was up, down, left, right,

641
00:32:23,035 --> 00:32:25,537
and then they'd be like, I don't understand why I'm dying.

642
00:32:25,537 --> 00:32:27,097
I don't understand why it's not working.

643
00:32:27,097 --> 00:32:29,038
Well, you have to be at 45 degree angle.

644
00:32:29,290 --> 00:32:29,591
What?

645
00:32:29,591 --> 00:32:32,032
They could not handle it.

646
00:32:32,032 --> 00:32:36,216
I got a lot of pressure to make it up, down, left, right.

647
00:32:36,216 --> 00:32:37,717
Just strangely.

648
00:32:37,717 --> 00:32:42,740
Let's see, what else is interesting in here?

649
00:32:42,740 --> 00:32:43,661
Oh, right.

650
00:32:43,661 --> 00:32:44,242
So eventually.

651
00:32:45,552 --> 00:32:51,134
Around this time, all of our development systems were replaced with an IBM PC.

652
00:32:51,134 --> 00:32:56,116
The original IBM PC, which I don't know if you are aware, the original IBM PC had no

653
00:32:56,116 --> 00:32:56,617
hard disk.

654
00:32:56,617 --> 00:32:59,518
It had a floppy disk.

655
00:32:59,518 --> 00:33:02,139
These had 8-inch floppy disks.

656
00:33:02,139 --> 00:33:08,061
The IBM PC had 5 1⁄4-inch, and they held a whopping 180K.

657
00:33:10,762 --> 00:33:13,162
and then they came out with double-sided ones

658
00:33:13,162 --> 00:33:15,703
that had 360K, and then eventually

659
00:33:15,703 --> 00:33:20,905
we got our first one megabyte hard drive.

660
00:33:20,905 --> 00:33:22,826
And oh my God, we thought,

661
00:33:22,826 --> 00:33:25,387
we never need any storage again.

662
00:33:25,387 --> 00:33:26,467
One megabyte.

663
00:33:26,467 --> 00:33:28,288
How are you ever gonna fill one megabyte?

664
00:33:28,288 --> 00:33:31,509
All right, you're laughing, but that's what it was.

665
00:33:31,509 --> 00:33:33,770
Anyway, that was a picture of me.

