00:34:36,639 --> 00:34:38,961
So moving on, sound.

689
00:34:38,961 --> 00:34:42,322
So basically, you've met me, you've met Jeff,

690
00:34:42,322 --> 00:34:44,724
but the third member of our team is the guy

691
00:34:44,724 --> 00:34:47,365
who did all of the sound and the speech,

692
00:34:47,365 --> 00:34:49,766
and that is Dave Thiel.

693
00:34:49,766 --> 00:34:51,047
Here's a picture of Dave Thiel.

694
00:34:51,047 --> 00:34:54,469
This was taken in the late 80s at a trade show.

695
00:34:55,109 --> 00:34:58,872
And I'm sure he would kill me if he knew I was showing this.

696
00:34:58,872 --> 00:35:03,356
Now Dave was, again, not as active a member of the team,

697
00:35:03,356 --> 00:35:05,879
but indispensable.

698
00:35:05,879 --> 00:35:11,103
And because, again, I was not arrogant about the game design,

699
00:35:11,103 --> 00:35:15,627
I gave him much free reign, as I did Jeff, to be creative

700
00:35:15,627 --> 00:35:16,508
and come up with things.

701
00:35:16,508 --> 00:35:20,351
So I do remember asking him for one particular sound,

702
00:35:20,351 --> 00:35:22,353
and that is when Kubrick jumps off the pyramid.

703
00:35:22,883 --> 00:35:24,906
uhhhhhhhhhhhhhhhh.

704
00:35:24,906 --> 00:35:26,707
I did ask him for that, which he delivered,

705
00:35:26,707 --> 00:35:29,470
but everything else was his invention.

706
00:35:29,470 --> 00:35:33,014
And the thing, of course, he's most known for

707
00:35:33,014 --> 00:35:36,237
is Kubert's speech.

708
00:35:36,237 --> 00:35:37,238
So how did that come about?

709
00:35:37,238 --> 00:35:41,022
Well, this is the pinball soundboard that we used.

710
00:35:41,022 --> 00:35:43,905
And you see where that arrow is, that yellow arrow,

711
00:35:43,905 --> 00:35:45,687
it's pointing to a chip called the Votrax chip.

712
00:35:46,475 --> 00:35:48,860
This was a chip that produces human phonemes.

713
00:35:48,860 --> 00:35:51,786
Human, like, you know, phoneme,

714
00:35:51,786 --> 00:35:54,832
everybody knows what a phoneme is, right?

715
00:35:55,437 --> 00:35:58,039
B-V, you know, and you string them together

716
00:35:58,039 --> 00:35:59,080
and you can get speech.

717
00:35:59,080 --> 00:36:04,305
Well, it's horribly monotonous and robot-like

718
00:36:04,305 --> 00:36:05,366
and does not sound good at all.

719
00:36:05,366 --> 00:36:08,769
And Dave just hated this chip and he hated using it.

720
00:36:08,769 --> 00:36:10,730
He had to get things, for pinball machines,

721
00:36:10,730 --> 00:36:13,953
he had to use it to get, say, things like bonus.

722
00:36:13,953 --> 00:36:15,935
And it just sounded like bogus all the time.

723
00:36:15,935 --> 00:36:20,859
So he hated this, but he had the genius idea

724
00:36:22,330 --> 00:36:24,943
to throw random numbers at that chip.

725
00:36:25,742 --> 00:36:31,926
and that is Qbert's speech. It's literally random phonemes. So people say all the time,

726
00:36:31,926 --> 00:36:39,131
you know, is Qbert cursing? And I go, he might be, because you put two, you put the right two

727
00:36:39,131 --> 00:36:44,675
phonemes together and he is cursing, but it's not programmed at all. It's just random. The only

728
00:36:44,675 --> 00:36:50,019
things that Qbert says, actual English, is when you turn the power switch on, he says,

729
00:36:50,019 --> 00:36:51,660
hello, I'm turned on.

730
00:36:52,441 --> 00:36:56,363
And then when you put your initials in the high score table, thank you very much,

731
00:36:56,363 --> 00:37:01,326
put your initials in the high score table, he says, bye-bye.

732
00:37:01,326 --> 00:37:09,311
So yeah, anyway, that's the story of the sounds. Now, naming him, I mean, all the way through this,

733
00:37:09,311 --> 00:37:15,075
I did not give the character a name. I did not give any character's name.

734
00:37:15,075 --> 00:37:18,096
Keep in mind, I'm just trying to make a game. I don't even know what I'm doing.

735
00:37:19,557 --> 00:37:22,680
This is some code, this is code from the original game,

736
00:37:22,680 --> 00:37:24,842
and I don't know if you can see it, maybe you can't see it,

737
00:37:24,842 --> 00:37:28,405
but you will not see the name Qbert anywhere.

738
00:37:28,405 --> 00:37:30,606
You will not see anybody's names because they didn't exist.

739
00:37:30,606 --> 00:37:33,789
The player was called P-L-Y-R, player,

740
00:37:33,789 --> 00:37:35,891
that's the only reference.

741
00:37:35,891 --> 00:37:40,195
The game itself is called Cubes, everything just says Cubes.

742
00:37:40,495 --> 00:37:45,599
Coily was called Chaser, C-H-S-R, in the code,

743
00:37:45,599 --> 00:37:46,720
because I had no games.

744
00:37:46,720 --> 00:37:50,764
Well, obviously, the game needed a name,

745
00:37:50,764 --> 00:37:52,345
and the character needed a name,

746
00:37:52,345 --> 00:37:55,188
and I think everybody, everybody agreed

747
00:37:55,188 --> 00:37:57,850
that the character name should be the name of the game.

748
00:37:57,850 --> 00:38:00,172
That was just something, everybody just had a feeling

749
00:38:00,172 --> 00:38:00,993
that's what it should be.

750
00:38:00,993 --> 00:38:06,078
So, actually, let me go to the next slide.

751
00:38:07,033 --> 00:38:09,033
So this is, I think this is from,

752
00:38:09,033 --> 00:38:10,634
and again, I don't know if you can see it or not,

753
00:38:10,634 --> 00:38:12,734
this is from Faster, Harder, More Challenging Qbert,

754
00:38:12,734 --> 00:38:15,615
and I can't even see it from here,

755
00:38:15,615 --> 00:38:18,956
but you'll see that there are references

756
00:38:18,956 --> 00:38:21,237
to Coily and Qbert in there,

757
00:38:21,237 --> 00:38:24,978
because that was after the original game.

758
00:38:26,864 --> 00:38:28,705
So Jeff was really good at naming things.

759
00:38:28,705 --> 00:38:30,146
So I let Jeff come up with names.

760
00:38:30,146 --> 00:38:33,969
So he came up with names like Ug and Wrong Way and Slick and Sam,

761
00:38:33,969 --> 00:38:37,191
which was a twist on Spick and Span.

762
00:38:37,191 --> 00:38:38,332
And I was just happy.

763
00:38:38,332 --> 00:38:40,573
I was thrilled, because I did not want that burden of having

764
00:38:40,573 --> 00:38:41,474
to name these characters.

765
00:38:41,474 --> 00:38:45,736
But when it came to the main character, the player character,

766
00:38:45,736 --> 00:38:47,477
it was like, what are we going to do?

767
00:38:47,477 --> 00:38:49,699
And Howie had an idea.

768
00:38:49,699 --> 00:38:52,180
Howie Rubin, our head of business development,

769
00:38:52,180 --> 00:38:53,201
had a great idea.

770
00:38:53,201 --> 00:38:55,643
He was like, let's call it the swearing balloon.

771
00:38:56,814 --> 00:38:59,737
And we were like, what?

772
00:38:59,737 --> 00:39:02,899
He's like, yeah, let's call it that.

773
00:39:02,899 --> 00:39:05,261
Well, Howie, how are you going to pronounce that?

774
00:39:05,261 --> 00:39:06,242
Well, you know what?

775
00:39:06,242 --> 00:39:08,784
If this game is as good as I think it is,

776
00:39:08,784 --> 00:39:09,905
people will find a way.

777
00:39:12,035 --> 00:39:14,637
And we were like, Howie, you're insane.

778
00:39:14,637 --> 00:39:18,280
But Howie insisted on putting the game out on test

779
00:39:18,280 --> 00:39:20,401
with these marquees.

780
00:39:20,401 --> 00:39:21,362
And then there's a handful, well,

781
00:39:21,362 --> 00:39:23,944
you might have all seen them, but back in the day,

782
00:39:23,944 --> 00:39:27,527
there were, I think, like a dozen of these marquees made

783
00:39:27,527 --> 00:39:28,908
for the game to be out on test with it.

784
00:39:28,908 --> 00:39:31,189
And we just thought he was nuts.

785
00:39:31,189 --> 00:39:33,971
But, you know, I think he eventually realized

786
00:39:33,971 --> 00:39:35,172
the error of his ways.

787
00:39:35,172 --> 00:39:36,733
It was probably not a smart idea.

788
00:39:37,867 --> 00:39:39,207
So, what are we gonna do?

789
00:39:39,207 --> 00:39:41,968
Well, I went around the office with a pad of paper,

790
00:39:41,968 --> 00:39:45,650
you know, notepad, and I polled everybody in the office.

791
00:39:45,650 --> 00:39:47,910
Got any ideas for the name of the game?

792
00:39:47,910 --> 00:39:50,011
I took everybody's suggestions.

793
00:39:50,011 --> 00:39:54,853
I had a sheet of about 50 names, and they were all terrible.

794
00:39:54,853 --> 00:39:57,694
I didn't like any of them.

795
00:39:57,694 --> 00:39:59,075
I only remember one from that.

796
00:39:59,075 --> 00:40:01,416
I wish I had that list, but I only remember one

797
00:40:01,416 --> 00:40:02,376
that was Arnie Aardvark.

798
00:40:02,376 --> 00:40:02,796
Am I like, meh, no.

799
00:40:02,796 --> 00:40:02,916
Anyway.

800
00:40:08,547 --> 00:40:15,010
Howie also had an idea of calling the game Why Me?

801
00:40:15,010 --> 00:40:15,890
But you know what?

802
00:40:15,890 --> 00:40:17,691
We needed a name for the character.

803
00:40:17,691 --> 00:40:19,732
So we had a meeting.

804
00:40:19,732 --> 00:40:21,833
And I will never forget this meeting.

805
00:40:21,833 --> 00:40:25,614
It was at least two hours, but it felt like an entire day.

806
00:40:25,614 --> 00:40:27,975
There were probably about 10 people sitting

807
00:40:27,975 --> 00:40:30,096
around the conference room.

808
00:40:30,096 --> 00:40:34,137
Middle managers was me, Jeff Lee, Ron, Howie,

809
00:40:34,137 --> 00:40:36,438
Rich Tracy was the art director for Gottlieb.

810
00:40:36,438 --> 00:40:37,359
There were some middle managers.

811
00:40:38,299 --> 00:40:42,100
all just sitting around trying to figure out what are we going to call this and it just went on and

812
00:40:42,100 --> 00:40:47,742
on and we're getting nowhere and you know it's exhausting it's exhausting to be in a meeting

813
00:40:47,742 --> 00:40:54,164
where you're just feeling like this is never going to work and then you know we're all ready to give

814
00:40:54,164 --> 00:41:00,366
up and um somebody I don't remember who it was somebody walks up to the the whiteboard and writes

815
00:41:00,366 --> 00:41:07,448
Hubert and we're like Hubert what's like why what's Hubert got to do with anything it's like

816
00:41:07,448 --> 00:41:07,808
I don't know

817
00:41:08,867 --> 00:41:10,348
You know, you got anything better?

818
00:41:10,348 --> 00:41:12,990
It's a cute name.

819
00:41:12,990 --> 00:41:16,373
And then somebody goes, wait a minute, wait a minute.

820
00:41:16,373 --> 00:41:20,056
And somebody else went up, and they erased the H,

821
00:41:20,056 --> 00:41:24,479
and they put a C. It's like, wait a minute, because cubes.

822
00:41:24,479 --> 00:41:25,460
It's got cube in it.

823
00:41:25,460 --> 00:41:27,302
Ooh, wait a minute.

824
00:41:27,302 --> 00:41:30,004
And everybody, you could feel like an energy start

825
00:41:30,004 --> 00:41:31,425
in the room, you know?

826
00:41:31,425 --> 00:41:32,306
It's like electric.

827
00:41:32,306 --> 00:41:35,628
And then somebody else goes up, and they put a Q

828
00:41:35,628 --> 00:41:36,689
instead of the CU.

829
00:41:36,689 --> 00:41:37,430
And we're like.

830
00:41:38,394 --> 00:41:40,156
I mean, it's like everybody's giddy.

831
00:41:40,156 --> 00:41:42,677
It's like, you know, it's like everybody's like two years old or something.

832
00:41:42,677 --> 00:41:45,980
And then, and then I think, I think it was Jeff Lee, but it might have been Rich Trace.

833
00:41:45,980 --> 00:41:50,964
It goes up and they change the dash to an asterisk and everybody just leaps out of their seats.

834
00:41:50,964 --> 00:41:54,066
And they're like, yes, yes, we found it.

835
00:41:54,066 --> 00:41:56,188
Actually, that may not have happened.

836
00:41:56,188 --> 00:41:57,329
I may be exaggerating.

837
00:41:58,490 --> 00:41:59,911
But it felt that way, it felt that way.

838
00:41:59,911 --> 00:42:02,374
But seriously, that's how it happened.

839
00:42:02,374 --> 00:42:04,215
It was just that we were in a meeting,

840
00:42:04,215 --> 00:42:07,459
and we had that, we finally came to that name.

841
00:42:07,459 --> 00:42:09,040
And literally though, it is true,

842
00:42:09,040 --> 00:42:10,982
everybody just agreed on it.

843
00:42:10,982 --> 00:42:13,224
It was like everybody knew it was right.

844
00:42:13,224 --> 00:42:18,830
The knocker, so the knocker is a really interesting feature.

845
00:42:18,830 --> 00:42:20,952
Sorry, I'm just curious how I'm doing on time here.

846
00:42:20,952 --> 00:42:21,673
Am I good?

847
00:42:23,678 --> 00:42:25,280
The knocker is an interesting feature.

848
00:42:25,280 --> 00:42:27,322
People love this feature, and so do I.

849
00:42:27,322 --> 00:42:28,943
But there's a little caveat to it

850
00:42:28,943 --> 00:42:31,685
in that I know that it could have been much better

851
00:42:31,685 --> 00:42:32,947
than it was, and I'll explain.

852
00:42:32,947 --> 00:42:36,850
The knocker, if you aren't aware,

853
00:42:36,850 --> 00:42:39,332
it's a little device that you find in pinball machines.

854
00:42:39,332 --> 00:42:40,573
It actually just, it's a piston.

855
00:42:40,573 --> 00:42:43,536
It just knocks the wood on the side of the machine

856
00:42:43,536 --> 00:42:45,077
to make a knock sound.

857
00:42:46,860 --> 00:42:50,763
And one of our engineering technicians came to me one day and said,

858
00:42:50,763 --> 00:42:54,645
you know, what do you think of the idea of having a knocker in the cabinet

859
00:42:54,645 --> 00:42:58,988
so when he falls off the pyramid, it's like he lands on the bottom?

860
00:42:58,988 --> 00:43:01,589
And I said, that's genius. I love that.

861
00:43:01,589 --> 00:43:03,571
So we tried it. We put it in.

862
00:43:03,571 --> 00:43:05,672
But, you know, the knock seemed wrong.

863
00:43:05,672 --> 00:43:09,174
It's like, you know, if a body lands in the bottom of a cabinet,

864
00:43:09,174 --> 00:43:10,615
it should be a thud, right?

865
00:43:10,615 --> 00:43:11,496
It shouldn't be a knock.

866
00:43:12,334 --> 00:43:18,879
So we sort of brainstormed, tried a few things, and what we came up with, we came up with a solution where if you took a little piece of foam

867
00:43:18,879 --> 00:43:24,923
where the piston hits the wood, just to soften that sound a little bit,

868
00:43:24,923 --> 00:43:29,246
it just worked perfectly. I mean, it literally sounded like a FUD,

869
00:43:29,246 --> 00:43:32,328
something like a sack of potatoes hitting the bottom of the cabinet.

870
00:43:32,689 --> 00:43:37,071
So we went to management, we told them about this, this is what we want, and they were like, well,

871
00:43:37,071 --> 00:43:43,754
we could put the knocker in, but the foam, it's going to cost like an extra $15 per cabinet,

872
00:43:43,754 --> 00:43:49,416
just in labor, to get somebody to go in and position it and glue it. Like, we're not going

873
00:43:49,416 --> 00:43:54,238
to do that. So they put the knocker in, but I know how much better it could have been. And

874
00:43:54,238 --> 00:43:58,200
I do recommend for people to do that if you have a cupid cabinet at home.

875
00:43:59,612 --> 00:44:03,054
All right, so the game started to feel complete.

876
00:44:03,054 --> 00:44:05,035
We're getting on into the late summer of 1982,

877
00:44:05,035 --> 00:44:08,717
and all the features were in I thought needed.

878
00:44:08,717 --> 00:44:11,618
And it really was just about tuning at this point.

879
00:44:11,618 --> 00:44:14,080
And of course, I have no experience,

880
00:44:14,080 --> 00:44:15,060
so I don't know what I'm doing.

881
00:44:15,060 --> 00:44:20,343
And I've been listening to the people in the office,

882
00:44:20,343 --> 00:44:24,825
because basically there are three ways that you do testing

883
00:44:24,825 --> 00:44:25,306
and tuning.

884
00:44:25,306 --> 00:44:25,626
Here we go.

885
00:44:26,663 --> 00:44:27,044
There we go.

886
00:44:27,044 --> 00:44:29,167
So in-house testing, which basically when

887
00:44:29,167 --> 00:44:31,570
the people you work with come by and play.

888
00:44:31,570 --> 00:44:33,112
So that's been happening all along.

889
00:44:33,112 --> 00:44:35,536
But people have been telling me

890
00:44:35,536 --> 00:44:37,658
it's too hard from the get-go.

891
00:44:37,658 --> 00:44:38,720
So I've been slowing it down.

892
00:44:38,720 --> 00:44:41,083
I've been trying to make it easier.

893
00:44:41,083 --> 00:44:44,267
It's just so, you know, to satisfy the people in the office.

894
00:44:45,243 --> 00:44:48,968
The second thing is location testing,

895
00:44:48,968 --> 00:44:50,971
which is something in the arcade industry we would do.

896
00:44:50,971 --> 00:44:53,936
We would take the cabinets, we'd put them into the arcades.

897
00:44:53,936 --> 00:44:56,740
We usually had an agreement with a particular arcade,

898
00:44:56,740 --> 00:44:57,962
and then they would collect the money,

899
00:44:57,962 --> 00:45:00,185
they'd report their coin earnings to us.

900
00:45:01,346 --> 00:45:04,827
and then they would maintain it for us.

901
00:45:04,827 --> 00:45:06,788
Now the reason that was important was because,

902
00:45:06,788 --> 00:45:09,409
see we're a manufacturer, Gottlieb made the games.

903
00:45:09,409 --> 00:45:13,350
They made their money off of selling the actual games.

904
00:45:13,350 --> 00:45:16,071
They didn't make money if people put quarters in.

905
00:45:16,071 --> 00:45:19,132
But the people we sold to, distributors,

906
00:45:19,132 --> 00:45:22,533
they made their money based on people putting quarters in.

907
00:45:22,533 --> 00:45:25,434
So it behooved us to have coin data

908
00:45:25,434 --> 00:45:28,075
that let them know this was gonna earn money.

909
00:45:28,815 --> 00:45:31,416
So that's pretty much how it worked.

910
00:45:31,416 --> 00:45:34,598
And Qbert went out into local arcades, and it did well.

911
00:45:34,598 --> 00:45:35,539
It earned money.

912
00:45:35,539 --> 00:45:37,760
It was very successful in that regard.

913
00:45:37,760 --> 00:45:39,221
But I would watch people play.

914
00:45:39,221 --> 00:45:40,282
I'd go to the arcade, and I'll never forget.

915
00:45:40,282 --> 00:45:41,863
There was this little girl.

916
00:45:41,863 --> 00:45:43,064
She might have been 12.

917
00:45:43,064 --> 00:45:45,525
She came up to the Qbert cabinet.

918
00:45:45,525 --> 00:45:48,287
She put her quarter in it, and she immediately just

919
00:45:48,287 --> 00:45:49,168
jumps right off the pyramid.

920
00:45:51,062 --> 00:45:52,202
Like, all right, give her a second.

921
00:45:52,202 --> 00:45:53,523
She might get it.

922
00:45:53,523 --> 00:45:55,905
Second life, boom, jumps right off the pyramid.

923
00:45:55,905 --> 00:45:58,547
Third life, boom, jumps right off the pyramid.

924
00:45:58,547 --> 00:46:00,348
I'm like, OK, this is not good.

925
00:46:00,348 --> 00:46:02,650
And she walks away.

926
00:46:02,650 --> 00:46:04,771
And then other people are coming by.

927
00:46:04,771 --> 00:46:07,413
But later, she came back, and she watched other people

928
00:46:07,413 --> 00:46:10,616
play it, and she went back to it.

929
00:46:10,616 --> 00:46:12,077
And this time, she didn't fall off the pyramid.

930
00:46:12,077 --> 00:46:14,839
So I was a little heartened by that,

931
00:46:14,839 --> 00:46:16,400
but I was very, very nervous.

932
00:46:16,400 --> 00:46:20,443
I really, you know.

933
00:46:21,515 --> 00:46:23,656
thought I had made some huge error.

934
00:46:23,656 --> 00:46:28,160
Anyway, the third way that we got information

935
00:46:28,160 --> 00:46:29,181
was focus groups.

936
00:46:29,181 --> 00:46:30,942
You know, you'd go to the mall and you'd say,

937
00:46:30,942 --> 00:46:33,144
hey, I'll give you 20 bucks if you come to this thing

938
00:46:33,144 --> 00:46:34,705
and try this video game out.

939
00:46:34,705 --> 00:46:37,948
And we were behind the one-way glass watching.

940
00:46:37,948 --> 00:46:40,230
And the thing I learned about focus groups,

941
00:46:40,230 --> 00:46:43,152
and I've done this a number of times throughout my career,

942
00:46:43,152 --> 00:46:45,033
not only for arcade games, but for home games,

943
00:46:45,033 --> 00:46:49,597
what people say and the way they behave

944
00:46:49,597 --> 00:46:50,578
while they're playing.

945
00:46:51,217 --> 00:46:52,979
Two completely different things.

946
00:46:52,979 --> 00:46:55,723
You can see people playing and they're getting into it

947
00:46:55,723 --> 00:46:57,946
and they really look like they're enjoying it.

948
00:46:57,946 --> 00:46:59,528
And then you ask them about it after,

949
00:46:59,528 --> 00:47:00,970
and they're like, yeah, it's okay.

950
00:47:00,970 --> 00:47:05,556
So I've always learned to really action,

951
00:47:05,556 --> 00:47:06,457
speak louder than words.

952
00:47:06,457 --> 00:47:08,801
I would recommend that.

953
00:47:09,955 --> 00:47:13,779
But I have to say, I did tune it easier.

954
00:47:13,779 --> 00:47:15,962
Management sort of pressured me.

955
00:47:15,962 --> 00:47:18,364
They just felt it was too hard, it was too challenging.

956
00:47:18,364 --> 00:47:22,789
A lot of people couldn't wrap their brains around it.

957
00:47:22,789 --> 00:47:23,930
But fall of 1982, October of 1982,

958
00:47:23,930 --> 00:47:27,034
Q-Bert started rolling off the production line.

959
00:47:28,795 --> 00:47:34,819
The first public real exposure to Qbert was at the trade show.

960
00:47:34,819 --> 00:47:41,042
We had an industry trade show in the fall in November of 1982 called the AMOA.

961
00:47:41,042 --> 00:47:45,385
Big big trade show for the coin op industry and Gottlieb went there, brought Qbert there,

962
00:47:45,385 --> 00:47:49,507
it was a big big deal, got a lot of press.

963
00:47:49,507 --> 00:47:50,488
So this is one of the.

964
00:47:52,589 --> 00:47:56,692
trade magazines that covered the press. This is the following January, all these pictures came out,

965
00:47:56,692 --> 00:47:59,434
but here's what's interesting about this one picture I think is hysterical.

966
00:47:59,434 --> 00:48:06,219
This Gottlieb's new Qubit game is the center of attraction as from left designer Jun-Yum,

967
00:48:06,219 --> 00:48:11,103
well he was the hardware designer, wasn't the game designer, then Gottlieb president Boyd Brown,

968
00:48:11,103 --> 00:48:13,625
of course they got him right, he's the president of the company.

969
00:48:14,723 --> 00:48:17,746
and programmers Warren Davis and Howard Rubin,

970
00:48:17,746 --> 00:48:21,029
how he's not a programmer, how he's the VP of business.

971
00:48:21,029 --> 00:48:23,511
So, you know, I learned again early in my career

972
00:48:23,511 --> 00:48:26,093
that don't trust everything you read

973
00:48:26,093 --> 00:48:28,315
because they get it wrong.

974
00:48:29,176 --> 00:48:31,097
But here's something they didn't get wrong.

975
00:48:31,097 --> 00:48:34,420
People judged Q-Bert, and they made a list

976
00:48:34,420 --> 00:48:37,222
of their picks of the show, and a lot of people

977
00:48:37,222 --> 00:48:38,503
put Q-Bert at the top of their list.

978
00:48:38,503 --> 00:48:42,245
It was really felt like it was gonna be a huge hit,

979
00:48:42,245 --> 00:48:43,246
and it was.

980
00:48:43,246 --> 00:48:44,727
I think what's most interesting about this

981
00:48:44,727 --> 00:48:47,589
is Popeye is number two.

982
00:48:47,589 --> 00:48:52,573
I don't know, does anybody remember the Popeye arcade game?

983
00:48:52,573 --> 00:48:54,754
I mean, you don't hear about it that much,

984
00:48:54,754 --> 00:48:57,576
but it was also, you know.

985
00:48:57,576 --> 00:48:57,856
Anyway.

986
00:49:00,990 --> 00:49:01,870
On to the next thing.

987
00:49:01,870 --> 00:49:04,471
So post-release problems.

988
00:49:04,471 --> 00:49:08,073
So it wasn't too long after the game was out

989
00:49:08,073 --> 00:49:10,654
that I started to get reports back,

990
00:49:10,654 --> 00:49:12,815
isolated reports, that people were playing

991
00:49:12,815 --> 00:49:14,736
for a very long time on a single quarter.

992
00:49:15,437 --> 00:49:16,918
And that's, you know, you don't want that.

993
00:49:16,918 --> 00:49:17,938
You don't want somebody to be on a machine

994
00:49:17,938 --> 00:49:19,659
because then other people aren't playing it

995
00:49:19,659 --> 00:49:21,361
and they're not, thank you.

996
00:49:21,361 --> 00:49:24,243
They're not, you know, the operators of the arcades

997
00:49:24,243 --> 00:49:25,824
aren't happy, the distributors aren't happy.

998
00:49:25,824 --> 00:49:30,166
So I started to doubt that the game was tuned well

999
00:49:30,166 --> 00:49:33,889
and I immediately set out to rectify that.

1000
00:49:33,889 --> 00:49:34,149
So.

1001
00:49:35,170 --> 00:49:41,835
And also, by the way, I should mention that there's a little secret in the tuning of the original Q-Bert.

1002
00:49:41,835 --> 00:49:45,898
If you notice, there are nine levels. There's a single-digit level.

1003
00:49:45,898 --> 00:49:51,262
Every four rounds is a new level. And it goes from one through nine, then it stays at nine.

1004
00:49:51,262 --> 00:49:55,885
The secret is, the tuning does not change after level five.

1005
00:49:56,727 --> 00:49:59,710
So levels five, six, seven, eight, and nine

1006
00:49:59,710 --> 00:50:03,995
are literally the exact same tuning tables.

1007
00:50:03,995 --> 00:50:06,798
Because I never imagined that anybody would get that far.

1008
00:50:06,798 --> 00:50:08,359
I couldn't get that far.

1009
00:50:08,359 --> 00:50:11,423
Nobody in the office could get that far.

1010
00:50:11,423 --> 00:50:12,924
That's why I was so freaked out

1011
00:50:12,924 --> 00:50:14,546
when people were getting that far.

1012
00:50:14,546 --> 00:50:16,288
So what were the problems?

1013
00:50:16,288 --> 00:50:17,169
The problems were.

1014
00:50:18,935 --> 00:50:19,576
It's too slow.

1015
00:50:19,576 --> 00:50:21,296
The very beginning, even today,

1016
00:50:21,296 --> 00:50:22,717
when I play the original Qbert,

1017
00:50:22,717 --> 00:50:24,377
I feel like he's floating from cube to cube.

1018
00:50:24,377 --> 00:50:25,698
It just feels very slow to me.

1019
00:50:25,698 --> 00:50:29,279
It's too easy.

1020
00:50:29,279 --> 00:50:31,100
Again, it's just my thought.

1021
00:50:31,100 --> 00:50:32,960
People were picking it up.

1022
00:50:32,960 --> 00:50:35,481
And it's not challenging enough.

1023
00:50:35,481 --> 00:50:37,002
So how do you rectify that?

1024
00:50:37,002 --> 00:50:38,602
Well, it's really very simple.

1025
00:50:38,602 --> 00:50:40,803
You make it faster, harder, and more challenging.

1026
00:50:40,803 --> 00:50:41,964
So that's what I set out to do.

1027
00:50:41,964 --> 00:50:44,965
And then, like, two months later,

1028
00:50:44,965 --> 00:50:47,986
I had faster, harder, more challenging Qbert.

1029
00:50:48,982 --> 00:50:53,204
So this game was different from the original Qbert.

1030
00:50:53,204 --> 00:50:55,384
I didn't want to call it Super Qbert or Qbert 2.

1031
00:50:55,384 --> 00:50:59,386
And it really wasn't a radical change.

1032
00:50:59,386 --> 00:51:03,847
It was more of a restructuring and a re-leveling.

1033
00:51:03,847 --> 00:51:05,028
Has anybody here ever played it?

1034
00:51:06,158 --> 00:51:07,939
No, oh, a few people.

1035
00:51:07,939 --> 00:51:10,060
The thing is, it was never released

1036
00:51:10,060 --> 00:51:11,461
because they put it out on test

1037
00:51:11,461 --> 00:51:12,822
right next to the original Qubert

1038
00:51:12,822 --> 00:51:14,643
when people were still learning Qubert.

1039
00:51:14,643 --> 00:51:16,765
So obviously, it did not test well.

1040
00:51:16,765 --> 00:51:18,406
My thought was they'd hold onto it

1041
00:51:18,406 --> 00:51:19,687
maybe a few months down the road,

1042
00:51:19,687 --> 00:51:21,368
they'd release it, but they did not.

1043
00:51:21,368 --> 00:51:26,211
And it stayed unreleased for many years until 1997

1044
00:51:26,211 --> 00:51:28,272
when I was working at Disney

1045
00:51:28,272 --> 00:51:31,394
and I met people who were involved in the MAME project

1046
00:51:31,394 --> 00:51:34,096
and they had emulated Gottlieb's hardware

1047
00:51:34,096 --> 00:51:35,757
so I just released the ROMs to them.

1048
00:51:36,723 --> 00:51:39,705
and it's been out in the public eye since 1997.

1049
00:51:39,705 --> 00:51:43,588
Anyway, you might notice here that it says Milestar

1050
00:51:43,588 --> 00:51:50,033
instead of Gottlieb, and that's because there was a point

1051
00:51:50,033 --> 00:51:52,235
after Qbert actually was released

1052
00:51:52,235 --> 00:51:54,597
that Gottlieb decided to change their names.

1053
00:51:54,597 --> 00:51:55,978
Gottlieb was owned by Columbia.

1054
00:51:56,985 --> 00:51:59,348
Columbia was bought by Coca-Cola,

1055
00:51:59,348 --> 00:52:02,232
so we had this big corporate overlord.

1056
00:52:02,232 --> 00:52:04,415
And I remember the day they came in

1057
00:52:04,415 --> 00:52:07,098
with a big cardboard sign that was covered with a sheet.

1058
00:52:07,098 --> 00:52:09,161
It was an all-hands meeting.

1059
00:52:09,161 --> 00:52:11,624
President of the company, Boyd Brown, is so proud.

1060
00:52:11,624 --> 00:52:13,086
He comes over and he goes.

1061
00:52:13,606 --> 00:52:16,369
I want to announce the new name of our company.

1062
00:52:16,369 --> 00:52:19,492
And he pulls the sheet down and there's the logo.

1063
00:52:19,492 --> 00:52:20,673
Milestar Electronics.

1064
00:52:20,673 --> 00:52:22,255
And the first thing I said out loud,

1065
00:52:22,255 --> 00:52:24,277
I don't think I knew I was saying it out loud.

1066
00:52:24,277 --> 00:52:30,644
I said, does anybody know that's rat slime spelled backwards?

1067
00:52:30,644 --> 00:52:35,108
And Boyd Brown was not amused.

1068
00:52:36,301 --> 00:52:37,621
But that's a true story.

1069
00:52:37,621 --> 00:52:41,062
And because they paid some consultant like $200,000

1070
00:52:41,062 --> 00:52:42,282
to come up with some cool name.

1071
00:52:42,282 --> 00:52:45,983
It's like, didn't even think of what it spells backwards?

1072
00:52:45,983 --> 00:52:48,064
Come on.

1073
00:52:48,064 --> 00:52:50,345
Faster, Harder, More Challenging Qbert had some things

1074
00:52:50,345 --> 00:52:53,625
like it had a bonus round where like a million Slicks and Sams

1075
00:52:53,625 --> 00:52:55,806
fall and you just got to grab as many as you can.

1076
00:52:55,806 --> 00:52:58,587
The levels were completely retuned.

1077
00:52:58,587 --> 00:53:00,327
So when you jump on squares.

1078
00:53:00,828 --> 00:53:03,152
rather than every level to get harder,

1079
00:53:03,152 --> 00:53:05,096
every round it gets harder.

1080
00:53:05,096 --> 00:53:06,719
And there's a whole lot of other things like that.

1081
00:53:06,719 --> 00:53:09,664
But let's talk about the aftermath of Qubit.

1082
00:53:09,664 --> 00:53:12,329
So Qubit came out, it turns out it was a success.

1083
00:53:13,028 --> 00:53:14,729
Who knew?

1084
00:53:14,729 --> 00:53:16,730
It was actually incredibly popular.

1085
00:53:16,730 --> 00:53:19,732
There was an article in Video Games Magazine

1086
00:53:19,732 --> 00:53:22,213
from a guy named Neil Tesser,

1087
00:53:22,213 --> 00:53:24,854
where he covered Joust and Qbert.

1088
00:53:24,854 --> 00:53:28,276
And the interesting thing was Joust was a Williams game,

1089
00:53:28,276 --> 00:53:29,477
John Newcomer designed it,

1090
00:53:29,477 --> 00:53:31,457
Bill Futson Reuter was the programmer,

1091
00:53:31,457 --> 00:53:34,239
but they named John Newcomer, Bill Futson Reuter,

1092
00:53:34,239 --> 00:53:36,840
Eugene Jarvis got named,

1093
00:53:36,840 --> 00:53:39,662
but they wouldn't name us.

1094
00:53:39,902 --> 00:53:47,007
So I was D. Ziner. That was me. I had a code name because Gottlieb would not let them use my name.

1095
00:53:47,007 --> 00:53:57,436
Jeff was R. Teast. That was Jeff. Very punny, huh? And then Dave Thiel was J. Walkman.

1096
00:53:57,436 --> 00:54:00,638
So I don't know where that came from.

1097
00:54:00,972 --> 00:54:06,234
After that, we sort of pressured Gottlieb to ease up on their secrecy.

1098
00:54:06,234 --> 00:54:08,675
You know, obviously, we knew why.

1099
00:54:08,675 --> 00:54:10,596
There was a lot of poaching going on in the industry.

1100
00:54:10,596 --> 00:54:12,997
They didn't want us to be known.

1101
00:54:12,997 --> 00:54:13,897
But they relented.

1102
00:54:13,897 --> 00:54:18,539
And faster, harder, more challenging Qubit actually has a credits page.

1103
00:54:18,539 --> 00:54:19,440
So we are credited.

1104
00:54:19,440 --> 00:54:25,002
And I didn't credit myself as designer, even though that was technically my role,

1105
00:54:25,002 --> 00:54:27,903
because I really felt like it was a team effort.

1106
00:54:27,903 --> 00:54:29,704
All of us owned that game.

1107
00:54:30,304 --> 00:54:36,448
So, let's see, a little, just a, I'm going to very quickly run through a lot of this,

1108
00:54:36,448 --> 00:54:39,690
some of the press that Kubrick got, because it really was everywhere in 1983.

1109
00:54:39,690 --> 00:54:46,695
In trade magazines, this is USA Today, that kind of blew me away, mainstream kind of stuff.

1110
00:54:46,695 --> 00:54:49,897
Of course, video game magazines is on the cover.

1111
00:54:52,010 --> 00:54:55,953
John Cougar, John Cougar mailing cam, hanging out on a QBert.

1112
00:54:55,953 --> 00:54:57,294
My God, you know?

1113
00:54:57,294 --> 00:55:01,377
This is a Japanese flyer.

1114
00:55:01,377 --> 00:55:05,220
The New Yorker, the New Yorker magazine talking about QBert.

1115
00:55:05,220 --> 00:55:08,603
And Glamour, Glamour magazine.

1116
00:55:08,603 --> 00:55:10,464
So yeah, I was like stunned.

1117
00:55:10,464 --> 00:55:13,066
Of course, I was completely anonymous.

1118
00:55:13,066 --> 00:55:15,648
You know, I didn't even know how to.

1119
00:55:17,750 --> 00:55:19,451
handle what I was seeing.

1120
00:55:19,451 --> 00:55:21,252
But I was just very content to sort of like

1121
00:55:21,252 --> 00:55:23,993
be in the background and watch the success of the game.

1122
00:55:23,993 --> 00:55:28,056
Then there were contests where they gave away

1123
00:55:28,056 --> 00:55:28,376
Cuber cabinets.

1124
00:55:28,376 --> 00:55:31,958
This is kind of interesting because the marketing department

1125
00:55:31,958 --> 00:55:35,120
really jumped on the licensing.

1126
00:55:35,888 --> 00:55:38,350
There were Qbert products everywhere.

1127
00:55:38,350 --> 00:55:42,674
You can see here, yeah, I mean, I could just go on and on.

1128
00:55:42,674 --> 00:55:47,438
There was a special version that management asked us to make

1129
00:55:47,438 --> 00:55:50,320
that featured Mellow Yellow.

1130
00:55:50,320 --> 00:55:52,442
So we actually had a Mellow Yellow can,

1131
00:55:52,442 --> 00:55:55,885
and if you remember the slide from the bonus round

1132
00:55:55,885 --> 00:55:57,787
of Faster, Harder, More Challenging Qbert,

1133
00:55:57,787 --> 00:56:01,410
we basically turned that cup into a Mellow Yellow can.

1134
00:56:02,050 --> 00:56:15,497
And somebody won this version. I think I heard from that person, but really interesting. Of course, there was a Saturday morning cartoon

1135
00:56:15,497 --> 00:56:18,078
Anybody remember this Wow

1136
00:56:18,838 --> 00:56:19,558
You can bring it down, yeah.

1137
00:56:19,558 --> 00:56:22,359
Yeah, this astonished us.

1138
00:56:22,359 --> 00:56:26,021
I think Jeff, Jeff Lee and I,

1139
00:56:26,021 --> 00:56:30,503
we got a lot of what are those guys smoking comments

1140
00:56:30,503 --> 00:56:32,323
when Qbert came out.

1141
00:56:32,323 --> 00:56:33,524
But when this came out,

1142
00:56:33,524 --> 00:56:35,685
I was like what are those guys smoking?

1143
00:56:36,986 --> 00:56:39,408
But, you know, listen, it is what it is.

1144
00:56:39,408 --> 00:56:43,151
All right, I'm just gonna finish up here.

1145
00:56:43,151 --> 00:56:46,233
You know, this is where the ports came out.

1146
00:56:46,233 --> 00:56:49,015
And of course, Qbert moved on.

1147
00:56:49,015 --> 00:56:52,397
They asked me if I wanted to do a sequel

1148
00:56:52,397 --> 00:56:54,939
after Faster, Harder, More Challenging, but I didn't.

1149
00:56:54,939 --> 00:56:57,341
I wanted to move on and do other things with my life.

1150
00:56:57,341 --> 00:56:59,563
But a guy named Neil Bernstein came to me and said,

1151
00:56:59,563 --> 00:57:02,085
I've got this idea for a Qbert sequel, do you mind?

1152
00:57:02,085 --> 00:57:04,166
And I said, no, please, have at it.

1153
00:57:04,166 --> 00:57:05,887
So he made a game called Qbert's Cubes.

1154
00:57:06,642 --> 00:57:09,805
That was an arcade game that Gottlieb actually released.

1155
00:57:09,805 --> 00:57:13,910
There was a pinball game called Qbert's Quest.

1156
00:57:13,910 --> 00:57:15,372
And Qbert didn't quite go away.

1157
00:57:15,372 --> 00:57:17,635
There was a little bit of a lull.

1158
00:57:17,635 --> 00:57:22,901
But then Qbert 3 came out for the Super Nintendo, Game Boy.

1159
00:57:24,627 --> 00:57:26,447
again in the 90s.

1160
00:57:26,447 --> 00:57:31,149
There's another little story, ironically involving the GDC.

1161
00:57:31,149 --> 00:57:32,249
I was at a GDC here.

1162
00:57:32,249 --> 00:57:34,530
I was working for Disney Interactive at the time,

1163
00:57:34,530 --> 00:57:37,011
but I was at a GDC in the late 90s.

1164
00:57:37,011 --> 00:57:37,951
I think it was 97, 98.

1165
00:57:37,951 --> 00:57:42,413
And I ran into people from Sony.

1166
00:57:42,413 --> 00:57:44,614
Sony obviously, well, I shouldn't say obviously.

1167
00:57:44,614 --> 00:57:48,435
Sony, okay, so Gottlieb was bought by Columbia Pictures,

1168
00:57:48,435 --> 00:57:49,856
which was bought by Coca-Cola.

1169
00:57:49,856 --> 00:57:53,537
Coca-Cola got rid of Gottlieb and shut it down.

1170
00:57:54,769 --> 00:57:56,310
Columbia Pictures was the owner.

1171
00:57:56,310 --> 00:57:57,891
Columbia was bought by Sony.

1172
00:57:57,891 --> 00:58:01,513
So in the 90s, Sony owned the rights to Qbert.

1173
00:58:01,513 --> 00:58:04,855
And I ran into some guys from Sony Computer Entertainment

1174
00:58:04,855 --> 00:58:06,135
of America, the games division,

1175
00:58:06,135 --> 00:58:08,617
and I said, you know, there's a lot of nostalgia

1176
00:58:08,617 --> 00:58:09,417
coming up in the 90s here.

1177
00:58:09,417 --> 00:58:12,699
There was a lot of nostalgia for old video games.

1178
00:58:12,699 --> 00:58:14,260
How come you're not doing anything with Qbert?

1179
00:58:14,260 --> 00:58:15,500
Because they owned the rights.

1180
00:58:15,500 --> 00:58:18,062
I never made any money off of it or anything.

1181
00:58:18,062 --> 00:58:20,203
How come you're not doing anything?

1182
00:58:20,203 --> 00:58:21,804
They said, what do you mean?

1183
00:58:22,465 --> 00:58:24,868
And I said, well, you own the rights to Qbert.

1184
00:58:24,868 --> 00:58:27,331
They were like, we own the rights to Qbert?

1185
00:58:27,331 --> 00:58:31,717
And they're like writing notes down,

1186
00:58:31,717 --> 00:58:33,078
and they're calling people on the phone.

1187
00:58:33,078 --> 00:58:37,123
They didn't know that they owned the rights to Qbert, which

1188
00:58:37,123 --> 00:58:39,886
until recently, I thought the same thing

1189
00:58:39,886 --> 00:58:41,849
was going on in recent years.

1190
00:58:43,180 --> 00:58:46,843
Anyway, a year later, Hasbro Interactive

1191
00:58:46,843 --> 00:58:50,465
came out with this version of Qubit.

1192
00:58:50,465 --> 00:58:54,628
So, and then in, oops, wait, I went backwards, sorry.

1193
00:58:54,628 --> 00:58:58,991
In more recent times, you've got this Qubit reboot,

1194
00:58:58,991 --> 00:59:01,813
it was a few years ago, and then of course,

1195
00:59:01,813 --> 00:59:04,695
you've got the movies, Wreck-It Ralph and Pixels.

1196
00:59:04,695 --> 00:59:09,538
I'm very astonished and sad that his nose has become flaccid.

1197
00:59:12,138 --> 00:59:14,394
I know he is getting old, but...

1198
00:59:15,603 --> 00:59:17,164
And I did talk a little bit about Milestar.

1199
00:59:17,164 --> 00:59:18,804
They went on, had some success,

1200
00:59:18,804 --> 00:59:22,205
but they closed their doors eventually.

1201
00:59:22,205 --> 00:59:24,065
And then this is a picture of the three of us,

1202
00:59:24,065 --> 00:59:26,846
the QBert team.

1203
00:59:26,846 --> 00:59:29,407
This was in 2016, I believe.

1204
00:59:29,407 --> 00:59:32,067
The first time the three of us had gotten together,

1205
00:59:32,067 --> 00:59:33,448
and it was a surprise.

1206
00:59:33,448 --> 00:59:35,308
Jeff, I flew into Chicago,

1207
00:59:35,308 --> 00:59:37,709
and Dave Thiel was there,

1208
00:59:37,709 --> 00:59:38,809
but he didn't know I was coming,

1209
00:59:38,809 --> 00:59:39,749
and Jeff drove me up,

1210
00:59:39,749 --> 00:59:41,750
and we had a little reunion.

1211
00:59:41,750 --> 00:59:43,110
And then a couple of years later,

1212
00:59:43,110 --> 00:59:44,370
we actually.

1213
00:59:44,570 --> 00:59:51,572
We were on a stage together for the first time in 30 some odd years at the Pinball Expo 2018, I think it was.

1214
00:59:51,572 --> 00:59:58,654
I just want to make very, very quickly, I've written a book, if you enjoy these stories.

1215
00:59:58,654 --> 01:00:02,255
I have many other stories that I tell about my entire arcade game career.

1216
01:00:02,255 --> 01:00:07,036
It's available wherever finer books are sold online.

1217
01:00:07,036 --> 01:00:12,918
And this is a cool thing. These cabinets you're looking at are 11 inches tall.

1218
01:00:13,758 --> 01:00:16,740
New Wave Toys makes these amazing replicas of games.

1219
01:00:16,740 --> 01:00:20,103
And the thing is, this one over here

1220
01:00:20,103 --> 01:00:23,725
is a perfect replica of the Cuber cabinet I have.

1221
01:00:23,725 --> 01:00:25,427
I'm told I'm out of time.

1222
01:00:25,427 --> 01:00:28,409
I'm gonna leave you with this one final image

1223
01:00:28,409 --> 01:00:29,670
to horrify your nightmares.

1224
01:00:29,670 --> 01:00:32,352
Thank you, thank you so, so much for coming.

1225
01:00:32,352 --> 01:00:33,453
I had a wonderful time.

1226
01:00:33,453 --> 01:00:34,934
Thank you, everybody.

